commit_message:
Enforce compute:update policy in V3 API

Now that compute/api.py:update() is no longer being called for instance
updates the policy check is no longer enforced.  This adds policy
checking back in at the V3 API level so that the compute:update policy will
continue to function as it did before.

This was fixed in I365ad8ac2845d914deefb841c314a50f4869dba0 for the V2
API.

Change-Id: I9caa3e10fe029569c6fd467e7b86103dd6590f9b
Closes-Bug: 1242955

commit_message:
Move get_all_tenants policy enforcement to API

Cleanup to move the enforcement of the get_all_tenants policy
enforcement to the API level. The all_tenants search option in
compute/api.py is only used to trigger policy enforcement while
the logic required by all_tenants (not specifying a project_id or
user_id filter) already resides in the servers API. The flag does
not need to be passed to the db level as it is ignored at that
level anyway.

Partially implements blueprint nova-v3-api

Change-Id: I5200c8912596ffbd32c5f7c6d74939782ff70260

AFAIK the commit message is incorrect:
http://openstack.10931.n7.nabble.com/cloud-init-root-password-from-meta-data-td19758.html

It is done by file injection (Different hypervisors does it a different way). Exposing an unhashed admin (root) password as metadata does not sounds safe to me, a slated hash might be safer, but different operating systems uses different hash types..

AFAIK it is not working with the cirros image, because  it has the /etc/shadow on the ram disk and not on the "main" disk before booting. (It also needs to be configured in nova)

AFAIK:
- cloud init does not do anything with setting up "the admin password", however the cloud-init has another ways to set up passwords. BTW on several images the password authentication is disabled by default.

So in our case the missing thing is the /etc/shadow on the first "real disk".

I voted with  -1 is bemuse of my first inline comment.'}, {'account_id': 5803, 'date': '2013-11-09 10:33:55.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

Do not expect the servers[0] is the server you created. Use the server returned by the cls.create_server explicitly."}, {'account_id': 6167, 'date': '2013-11-12 21:42:42.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

(1 inline comment)

Now, need to rebase because If09fc09f77d27a48dc19dd2dbc47ea460b0c7920 is merged."}, {'account_id': 5586, 'date': '2013-11-15 07:48:17.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: (2 inline comments)

hi, afazekas.
thanks for your review and comment.
Yes, you are right. cloud init does not do anything with setting up "the admin password", however the cloud-init has another ways to set up passwords. 
(hypervisor can set the admin password and just it only supported by xen 
  https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/HypervisorSupportMatrix#Hypervisor_feature_support_matrix , other hypervisor need do this in other ways.)

But here, we get the password from instance[system_metadata]. and How is the password set in system_metadata? 
It is set via the api added by this patch: https://review.openstack.org/#/c/17274/
Who set the password via this API?
I guess it is cloud_init and other scripts (that access metadata server) in vm. If I'm wrong, correct me please.

So here, whether we can get pwd just depends on if vm has sent pwd to metadata server or not, and it has nothing to do with whether it is set to vm.'}, {'account_id': 5586, 'date': '2013-11-15 07:57:06.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 3.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-11-15 08:44:30.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Works for me

commit_message:
add tests for server_password

this adds tests for the following request:
GET /v2/{tenant_id}/servers/{server_id}/os-server-password
DELETE /v2/{tenant_id}/servers/{server_id}/os-server-password

this requires hypervisors or cloud_init script support, so
we just check the response code here rather than check the
content of the response

Change-Id: I641f7ca92fd7cb73df2f5b9cef34af53206ba8f7

commit_message:
Cache compute node info in Hypervisor api

When extend hypervisor api, it would be much better to cache the
compute node info like is done for instance and flavor requests.

Partially implement blueprint pci-api-support

Change-Id: I73a96db7beb4cc0f017008f81e9f671382ad9105

commit_message:
Remove duplicate entries

oslo.config and oslo.messaging are listed twice in the projects list.
With the new cleaner requirements integration script, this causes an
error.

commit_message:
add role negative tests

make a seperate file test_roles_negative.py and move exist negative tests
over to it,also add some negative tests to it

- test_delete_role_by_unauthorized_user
- test_delete_role_request_without_token
- test_delete_role_non_existent
- test_create_role_by_unauthorized_user
- test_create_role_request_without_token

Change-Id: If9f9ef67647d3ab0cfa91c2cbede1412a316148f

[{'created': '2013-11-12 14:30:37.000000000', 'message': 'Change benchmark config format

The patch improves the benchmark config format in that it moves some technical
parameters for each scenario run (like "times", "tenants" etc.) in a special
"config" section and also renames the "concurrent" parameter to "active_users",
which is way more clear for the end-user.

A typical benchmark config now would look like this:

"benchmark": {
    "NovaServers.boot_and_delete_server": [
        {"args": {"flavor_id": 1,
                  "image_id": "73257560-c59b-4275-a1ec-ab140e5b9979"},
         "execution": "continuous",
         "config": {"times": 10, "active_users": 2,
                    "tenants": 3, "users_per_tenant": 2}}
    ]
}

The new mandatory "execution" parameter indicates the means of scenario
execution and can now be set to only one value, namely "continuous". Another
execution type, "periodic", will be implemented in another patch.

The patch also improves unittest coverage for possible benchmark config issues.

Blueprint test-engine
Change-Id: Iabc90838aa8ad9cb44d73892852ed21c652ad274

commit_message:
Change benchmark config format

The patch improves the benchmark config format in that it moves some technical
parameters for each scenario run (like "times", "tenants" etc.) in a special
"config" section and also renames the "concurrent" parameter to "active_users",
which is way more clear for the end-user.

A typical benchmark config now would look like this:

"benchmark": {
    "NovaServers.boot_and_delete_server": [
        {"args": {"flavor_id": 1,
                  "image_id": "73257560-c59b-4275-a1ec-ab140e5b9979"},
         "execution": "continuous",
         "config": {"times": 10, "active_users": 2,
                    "tenants": 3, "users_per_tenant": 2}}
    ]
}

The new mandatory "execution" parameter indicates the means of scenario
execution and can now be set to only one value, namely "continuous". Another
execution type, "periodic", will be implemented in another patch.

The patch also improves unittest coverage for possible benchmark config issues
and replaces some nested mock calls with a better wrapper syntax.

Blueprint flexible-benchmark-config
Change-Id: Iabc90838aa8ad9cb44d73892852ed21c652ad274

commit_message:
Fixing space issues between " and ]

When we are using '[' aka. ``test`` , before the closing ']'
we need to use a space.

Otherwise the commands return with '2' so the "expression" will be a constant
false.

Change-Id: I673762e802c28335e03390b6608cf6bbee6aaba6

[{'created': '2013-11-18 22:16:48.000000000', 'message': 'Fix stackforge_libs installation step

When stackforge_libs is enabled, the WSME and Pecan libraries
are checked out from stackforge and installed from source instead of
pip. This change introduces a new function to perform the installation
without attempting to sync the global requirements list, since the
version of setup.py in the global requirements repository breaks the
dependencies for WSME (there is no ipaddr library in python 2, so we
need to install it, but under python 3 where it is part of the stdlib we
cannot include it in the requirements).

Fixes bug 1252488

Change-Id: I58357757ac67a919bf70178b76f65fa0a9e16242
'}]
commit_message:
Fix stackforge_libs installation step

When stackforge_libs is enabled, the WSME and Pecan libraries
are checked out from stackforge and installed from source instead of
pip. This change introduces a new function to perform the installation
without attempting to sync the global requirements list, since the
version of setup.py in the global requirements repository breaks the
dependencies for WSME (there is no ipaddr library in python 2, so we
need to install it, but under python 3 where it is part of the stdlib we
cannot include it in the requirements).

Fixes bug 1252488

commit_message:
Fix sqlalchemy DateTime type usage

In migration f9263d6df56_remove_dhcp_lease there is mistake in
DateTime type usage for mysql, used sa.DATETIME() instead of
sa.DateTime()

Closes-Bug: #1250405

Change-Id: I41fcd3babc64e3307895a92f03c7417577fa7b1d

commit_message:
Fix OVS agent reclaims local VLAN

If a port disappears on an OVS agent, the port is removed of the lvm
vif_ports list. And if it's the last port of the network on this agent,
the network local VLAN is reclaim.

Change-Id: I07e03107eb86a84eeb8e4d06f27a1d2fbd7cea57
Closes-Bug: #1252284

'}, {'account_id': 6072, 'date': '2013-09-10 19:42:24.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

(2 inline comments)

Beside the inline commend I think it might be better to create subresource of ports that could be deleted with DELETE method.

That is however just an opinion."}, {'account_id': 841, 'date': '2013-09-11 05:54:12.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: (1 inline comment)

The behavior of extra_dhcp_opts attribute is very tricky and it is completely different from the all other attributes in Neutron.

When updating the extra_dhcp_opts attribute, we must post an incremental difference. This means that there is a dependency across update operations and it is not a REST way. IMO, to enhance the behavior of this feature, we should discuss the complete spec of the behavior rathen a code. We also need to document this feature in networking API guide.
The spec is not good from the point of view of the consistency.
In the review of the initial implementation, I opposed to the spec but Mark and other related people accepts the behavior.


Returning to this review.

action=clear does not work in this case. extra_dhcp_opts is a list attribute and the goal of this patch is just remove some existing extra dhcp option.

A string value of "null" is not appropriate. On the API (JSON) layer {'opt_name': 'xxxx', 'opt_value': None} is better.
I am not sure a string "null" is a valid DHCP option value, but we should avoid such constraints as much as possible.
Of course this needs the client command update, but it doesn't matter. The client command is completely different topic from the point of the view of the server side review.

In addition, we should consider a way to clear (= set an empty list) extra_dhcp_opts.
extra_dhcp_opts extension does not reset extra dhcp options to an empty list by sending '{"extra_dhcp_opts": None}'.
This is a usual way to clear (= set empty) the attribute, but this extension does not.'}, {'account_id': 841, 'date': '2013-09-11 05:54:18.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

"}, {'account_id': 2592, 'date': '2013-09-11 18:26:41.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

(2 inline comments)

"}, {'account_id': 5572, 'date': '2013-09-12 19:24:48.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 5572, 'date': '2013-09-12 19:25:00.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: (4 inline comments)

commit_message:
Adds delete of a extra_dhcp_opt on a port

Add support for delete of extra_dhcp_opt(s) on a port. Where
[{'opt_name': 'opt_to_delete', 'opt_value': None}].

Closes-Bug: #1228008

Change-Id: I75baeff91575cac6546fe2cc6fcf7a0d8e92853f

commit_message:
Adds tests, fixes Radware LBaaS driver as a result

Adding more tests for Radware LBaaS driver.
Adding new exception module for the Radware lbaas driver.
The base radware lbaas exception, called RadwareLBaasException,
Several specific exceptions for different failures.
Driver was changed for using new exceptions as well.
Changing the way OperationsHandler obtains context.
Always waiting 1 second before handling the operation
next time, to prevent busy-wait requests on vDirect.
Several code optimizations were done as well.

Change-Id: I15f7845fc2575eedb62c47d15ee6c1cea08e22f5
Closes-Bug: #1236741

Hi Justin,

Your concern is fair enough. As far as I check the neutron code, context.used/tenant are not used anywhere. We need to check this carefully.

Thanks for your feedback.

I also looked Context class in other projects (oslo, nova, cinder) but I am not sure if tenant/user attribute in Context object should be ID or name.

I think there are several options. option a is my current choice, but option b is worth considered.

- (option a) Store tenant/user name in context.tenant/user
- (option b) Keep context.tenant/user unchanged and change to_dict() to return tenant/user_name for tenant/user fields.
- (option c) Output tenant/user UUID in log messages. It changes nothing other than request_id but log messages are not human friendly.

Any suggestions will be appreciated.'}, {'account_id': 841, 'date': '2013-10-17 05:44:04.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-10-17 06:27:00.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: Doesn't seem to work

commit_message:
Add request-id to log messages

request-id needs to be stored in thread local store to allow
openstack.common.log use request-id.
tenant_name and user_name are added to the context so that
they can be logged by customizing the log format.

Also replaces 'cxt' with 'ctx' in test_neutron_context.py.
Previously both 'ctx' and 'cxt' are used mixed in one file.

Change-Id: Ib921585e648e92491c1366bc0ad26a6ae71e2fc9
Partial-Bug: #1239923

revisions:
[{'created': '2013-10-28 17:27:13.000000000', 'message': "Make sure that we ioudly skip versioned 2.6 libs

We skip a few libs that are only needed on 2.6. There are two issues with this.
One is that we do it silently skip thm, so people think it's a bug. The second
is that we are only skipping based on name matching, not on requirement
lines.

Change-Id: If64e4b2ee6696a0531e3ed6099e63372d47bc851

commit_message:
Base python 2.7 skip list on parsed names

We keep a list of libraries that should only be installed on python 2.6,
but the check to see if a requirement matches that list was only doing
a simple string equality, which would miss attempts to install version
specified instances of one of them.

Instead, use pkg_resources to parse the potential requirements line and
operate on the parsed project name.

Change-Id: If64e4b2ee6696a0531e3ed6099e63372d47bc851

commit_message:
[1246251] MGMT, Storage nets have no gateway

Management and storage networks must have no gateway for both
Neutron and Nova-Network providers.
Floating network must have no gateway in case of Nova-Network.
Gateway field is set to 'None' for them.
'network_size' field is relevant for fixed network only.
Small refactoring of networking-related tests.

Closes-Bug: #1246251
Change-Id: Icfa425c094e3d0c45b0a9e979cdf3f0c719d106d

commit_message:
Use POST in bulk-delete

The DELETE verb applies to a single resource, and doesn't define any
semantics for the body.

http://www.w3.org/Protocols/rfc2616/rfc2616-sec9.html#sec9.7

The swift Bulk Delete command affects multiple resources specified in a
DELETE body.

http://docs.openstack.org/developer/swift/misc.html#module-swift.common.middleware.bulk

While Bulk Delete is a welcome operation, its usage of DELETE is
unusual: affecting multiple resources and relying on reading content.

More typically, such an operation employs POST (or PUT), which folks
including api-craft usually agree is the best "catch-all" verb for
behaviors such as those affecting multiple resources. That's the TL;DR;
of the thread below.

https://groups.google.com/forum/#!searchin/api-craft/Regarding$20Bulk$20actions/api-craft/wY-W1NdZDRs/7YDwMhCR608J

Note that this topic isn't nasal or abstract. The current behavior is
unsupported using the built-in java http client. Even if third-party
libraries can work around this behavior, it is probably best to not be a
snowflake wrt http verb semantics where possible!

http://stackoverflow.com/questions/9100776/http-delete-with-request-body-issues

DocImpact

Closes-Bug: #1232787
Change-Id: I0fc74c85618fe4dd7ff5e7f9756c7f6f67aa0465

commit_message:
Add support for extend volume in GPFS vol driver

Add support for extend volume support to the GPFS volume
driver.

Ensure that requested volume size is implemented for each
of the volume creation paths.

Replace instances where units.GiB could be used but was not.

Implements: blueprint gpfs-extend-volume-support
Change-Id: I79295205f4147fca109f5cb59497a6e1fbe6d296

commit_message:
Move libvirt flags to libvirt group (cont.)

Following Michael's progress on blueprint libvirt-opts-group:

* Rename libvirt_type virt_type and move to libvirt group.
* Rename libvirt_uri conn_uri and move to libvirt group.

Move to libvirt group:

* libvirt_inject_password
* libvirt_inject_key
* libvirt_inject_partition
* libvirt_vif_driver
* libvirt_volume_drivers
* libvirt_disk_prefix
* libvirt_wait_soft_reboot_seconds
* libvirt_non_blocking
* libvirt_cpu_mode
* libvirt_cpu_model
* libvirt_snapshots_directory

Move libvirt_nonblocking to libvirt group and rename to
libvirt_non_blocking, correcting typo. Changes will be picked
up in output next time docs autoconfig is run.

Change-Id: Idbaa7d6c7ab3c4c2df56d0ad995214902fe6c115
Closes-Bug: #1253812

commit_message:
Renamed docker_registry_default_port flag

The docker_registry_default_port flag has been renamed
registry_default_port to reflect that namespacing is
already provided via the context of the "docker" group
that it appears in.

Change-Id: Ia26f747a67b36fb96f72d3cc98016342e124b152
Closes-Bug: #1249441

commit_message:
all_tenants=0 should not return instances from all tenants

Fixes set up of server list filters so specifying all_tenants=0
or all_tenants=False when requesting a list of servers does not
result in instances from all tenants being returned.

Change-Id: I72575e4e2cf9019cfd5bf3b07ada53cadf2001e2
Closes-Bug: #1240347

commit_message:
Update the management url for every fetched token

management_url was originally set once and never changed so that when
specifying an endpoint it wasn't later overridden by the service
catalog. This behaviour would prevent the management_url from being
updated when the client was reauthenticated.

Change-Id: I2fa41e2ae1b853bbb254698cf94b9314eb0f0903
Closes-bug: 1252927

commit_message:
Sync log from oslo

5fef5a8105 allow keeping of existing loggers with fileConfig
fb8075a19d Add amqp=WARN,qpid=WARN to default_log_levels
4654a5d247 Don't override default value for eventlet.wsgi.server logging
41ddd7a975 _get_log_file_path explictly return, when logfile/logdire unset
e12e6b45f8 Make openstack.common.log Python 3 compatible
572cfecb4d Make Messages unicode before hitting logging
3243cdfbe9 python3: handle module moves in log

DocImpact

Change-Id: I7bd940a9a2dd4af3d876f2acc650f18675ca177b

[{'created': '2013-11-21 17:49:06.000000000', 'message': "Fix PATH in pypi-mirror cron job

The PATH in pypi-mirror's cron job was the system default, which does
not have /usr/local/bin. Because of this, we weren't finding run-mirror
and failing every time.

Change-Id: I657e8a97232cc63e5d7f34d989e51ab9bec1da6e
"}]
commit_message:
Fix PATH in pypi-mirror cron job

The PATH in pypi-mirror's cron job was the system default, which does
not have /usr/local/bin. Because of this, we weren't finding run-mirror
and failing every time.

Change-Id: I657e8a97232cc63e5d7f34d989e51ab9bec1da6e

commit_message:
Add the nova V3 api endpoint

This is a separate endpoint and is required by some tempest tests, there
still appears to be problems using the V3 API but this at least allows
the the V3 API to be found.

Change-Id: I302c3341720520abd2b58b8b43e2f794d5e3b086

commit_message:
Rename InstanceType exceptions to Flavor

Goes through and renames the various exceptions with InstanceType in the
name or message string to use Flavor instead.

Part of bp flavor-instance-type-dedup

Change-Id: I59d77086af0747f95ad61a569e784b766c8909a9

commit_message:
Added support for running the tests under PyPy with tox

This is a precursor to having them run under check and gate.

Change-Id: I377f0a4dddc063402db7486789f7c00847013eec

[{'created': '2013-11-21 09:58:09.000000000', 'message': 'Add contextual markers to BatchAction messages

BatchAction message is used for both present (table action menu)
and past (completion message) and there is no way that translators
use different texts for present and passt messages.
This commit add contextual markers to the message strings and allows
translators to use different texts for message in BatchAction.

Change-Id: Ie6438730386fc2cca18704354d5cf5f5b71cd494
Closes-Bug: #1252082
'}]
commit_message:
Add contextual markers to BatchAction messages

BatchAction message is used for both present (table action menu)
and past (completion message) and there is no way that translators
use different texts for present and passt messages.
This commit add contextual markers to the message strings and allows
translators to use different texts for message in BatchAction.

Change-Id: Ie6438730386fc2cca18704354d5cf5f5b71cd494
Closes-Bug: #1252082

Neutron Client allows creation of VIP by specifying only

commit_message:
VIP creation fails if ip address is not specified.

Neutron Client allows creation of VIP by specifying only
a subnet. In that case a free ip from that subnet will be
asigned.
When creating the VIP from Horizon, if the ip address is not
set on them form, the request for VIP creation will include
an empty address and fail.
If the address is not set or empty, don't send that key
since it's not mandatory.

Change-Id: Id9b8f4aa187eae65f5b87c742309e0e39c804208
Closes-Bug: #1252811

commit_message:
fix help message of "create flavor"

The help text in "Flavor Info" tab of "Create Flavor" workflow is wrong.
It says "From here you can create a new flavor to organize projects.",
but flavor organizes not "project" but "instance resources".

Change-Id: I77ee55b2c35a8d743d318e699fb45f4dc8ed4251
Closes-Bug: #1252076

commit_message:
Fix up python 3.3 incompatabilities

Make the python 3.3 testing work by selectively
disabling & including eventlet, switch to testtools
and testrepository which has 2.6, 2.7, 3.2+ unified
testing support so that we can correctly run our
tests in all supported python versions.

Closes-Bug: #1251660
Co-authored-by: Alexander Gorodnev <agorodnev@griddynamics.com>
Change-Id: I23b6f04387cfd3bf6b5a044edffa446ca897ce3a

commit_message:
Remove suffixes from LVM brick test vgs output

When fake_execute() is called to retrieve volume group information, the
--nosuffix flag is passed but ignored.  This patch honors the nosuffix
flag and removes the unit suffix from the volume group sizes in the
returned output.

Change-Id: I45f41bc58f4ffb4bd527336c0f760350cff7c355

commit_message:
Subject: Separate quotas neg tests to _negative file

According to the requirement that all negative tests must be added to a
negative test file, I added a new test file and copied all the quotas negative
test cases in it.

Other issues:
-------------
* Some test lacked the 'negative' flag, so it was also added.
* I left afazekas's TODO comment as is.
* 2 test cases remained skipped because of bug 1186354

Change-Id: Ide5f9e58b5d6ae2e97926b281f63f79f8956ae23

'}, {'account_id': 9318, 'date': '2013-11-09 21:23:51.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

pyparsing 2.x breaks the dot_parser module, which means state_graph.py won't always work. 1.5.7 seems to be the last version in the 1.x series of pyparsing.


(.venv)[jeff@omniscience tools]$ python state_graph.py -h
Couldn't import dot_parser, loading of dot files will not be possible.
Usage: state_graph.py [options]

Options:
  -h, --help            show this help message and exit
  -f FILE, --file=FILE  write svg to FILE
  -t, --tasks           use task state transitions
  -T FORMAT, --format=FORMAT
                        output in given format
(.venv)[jeff@omniscience tools]$ python
Python 2.7.5 (default, Oct  8 2013, 12:19:40) 
[GCC 4.8.1 20130603 (Red Hat 4.8.1-1)] on linux2
Type "help", "copyright", "credits" or "license" for more information.

>>> import dot_parser
Traceback (most recent call last):
  File "<console>", line 1, in <module>
  File "/home/jeff/git/taskflow/.venv/lib/python2.7/site-packages/dot_parser.py", line 25, in <module>
    from pyparsing import ( nestedExpr, Literal, CaselessLiteral, Word, Upcase, OneOrMore, ZeroOrMore,
ImportError: cannot import name _noncomma
>>> 
(.venv)[jeff@omniscience tools]$ pip freeze | grep pyparsing
pyparsing==2.0.1
(.venv)[jeff@omniscience tools]$ nl -ba /home/jeff/git/taskflow/.venv/lib/python2.7/site-packages/dot_parser.py | egrep '^[[:space:]]+2[5-8][[:space:]]'
    25	from pyparsing import ( nestedExpr, Literal, CaselessLiteral, Word, Upcase, OneOrMore, ZeroOrMore,
    26	    Forward, NotAny, delimitedList, oneOf, Group, Optional, Combine, alphas, nums,
    27	    restOfLine, cStyleComment, nums, alphanums, printables, empty, quotedString,
    28	    ParseException, ParseResults, CharsNotIn, _noncomma, dblQuotedString, QuotedString, ParserElement )
(.venv)[jeff@omniscience tools]$ pip uninstall pyparsing
Uninstalling pyparsing:
  /home/jeff/git/taskflow/.venv/lib/python2.7/site-packages/pyparsing-2.0.1-py2.7.egg-info
  /home/jeff/git/taskflow/.venv/lib/python2.7/site-packages/pyparsing.py
  /home/jeff/git/taskflow/.venv/lib/python2.7/site-packages/pyparsing.pyc
Proceed (y/n)? y
  Successfully uninstalled pyparsing
(.venv)[jeff@omniscience tools]$ pip install 'pyparsing<=1.5.7'
Downloading/unpacking pyparsing<=1.5.7

Usage: state_graph.py [options]

Options:
  -h, --help            show this help message and exit

                        output in given format'}, {'account_id': 7366, 'date': '2013-11-10 14:33:36.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Do not merge

I still have some doubt about these arguments, In v1 shell.py, I saw it is allowed to use "--display_description" argument in 
"do_create" method, but in "do_rename" method, it not support "--display_description", but in v2 shell.py, the "do_rename" method would support "--display_description" argument. These are many such cases in V1 and V2 shell.py.

I thinks we should unify these arguments, all of methods should support these SUPPRESS arguments or not.'}, {'account_id': 2759, 'date': '2013-09-11 07:07:21.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

The general rule of thumb is we don't break backwards compatibility. Period.

About the inconsistency between v1 and v2 supported argument, some are intended (to ditch legacy argument in new version API) and some are simply bugs. So my suggestion is we make a list of v1/v2 arguments inconsistency and then send it to mailing list, folks who have better understanding of the CLI client history can provide more insights on how to deal with current situation."}, {'account_id': 8278, 'date': '2013-09-11 09:45:12.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

commit_message:
Remove no-use arguments and add unit test cases

These are some no-use arguments in client v2 shell.py. This patch
removes these no-use arguments and add some related unit test cases.

Fixes bug 1221611

Change-Id: Ifa65a34df3e9b5a7ebe928895160e2f57bced582

commit_message:
baremetal: refactor out powervm dependency

For some reason part of the baremetal driver was
importing some of the common modules from the
powervm driver. This change moves the code baremetal
was using into a new baremetal only module to remove
the strange cross driver dependency.

Change-Id: Id5f48bed4ecff7cd776346b34c34f3a2094f2296

commit_message:
Add valid check and unit tests on quota class

1.Cinder quota class hard_limits value should larger than -1 (-1 is a flag
value for unlimited).
2.Add unit tests for quota class.

Closes-bug: #1245360

Change-Id: Ie483db1bdbd4fac875de26abab8ebebd96f4938b

[{'created': '2013-11-18 09:01:16.000000000', 'message': 'Create snapshot throws 500 Internal Error

The server doesn't check whether the parameter "volume_id" is in request body.
So the 500 error has been thrown.

We should catch the KeyError and transfer the KeyError to 400(HTTPBadRequest)
instead of 500.

Change-Id: I8a1dde1fd6ed820b39995af434efacc2a27c9604
Closes-Bug: #1252179
'}]
commit_message:
Create snapshot throws 500 Internal Error

The server doesn't check whether the parameter "volume_id" is in request body.
So the 500 error has been thrown.

We should catch the KeyError and transfer the KeyError to 400(HTTPBadRequest)
instead of 500.

Change-Id: I8a1dde1fd6ed820b39995af434efacc2a27c9604
Closes-Bug: #1252179

commit_message:
Add missing vpnaas class in example manifest

examples/neutron was missing neutron::agents::vpnaas which is useful
for people wanting to write manifests based on puppet-neutron module.

Change-Id: I374c4315472d46397c1cc2152bd35e1cdfd7336a
Signed-off-by: Emilien Macchi <emilien.macchi@enovance.com>

[{'created': '2013-11-14 19:02:28.000000000', 'message': 'Import filter and app into namespace correctly

The module used to simply "import swift", and then reference
the classes:

    swift.common.middleware.catch_errors.CatchErrorsMiddleware
    swift.proxy.server.Application

in order to very that the WSGI services loaded the proper filters and
apps.

However, those references only happen to work, as the WSGI loading
would properly import the rest of the path so that the namespace
reference would be okay. If the WSGI configuration were to change, or
if the behavior of WSGI broke, instead of of seeing the actual failure
condition, a module attribute error would result instead:

    AttributeError: 'module' object has no attribute 'middleware'

The referenced names are now properly imported with this change to
avoid misleading error conditions.

commit_message:
Import filter and app into namespace correctly

The module used to simply "import swift", and then reference
the classes:

    swift.common.middleware.catch_errors.CatchErrorsMiddleware
    swift.proxy.server.Application

in order to very that the WSGI services loaded the proper filters and
apps.

However, those references only happen to work, as the WSGI loading
would properly import the rest of the path so that the namespace
reference would be okay. If the WSGI configuration were to change, or
if the behavior of WSGI broke, instead of of seeing the actual failure
condition, a module attribute error would result instead:

    AttributeError: 'module' object has no attribute 'middleware'

The referenced names are now properly imported with this change to
avoid misleading error conditions.

Change-Id: Ifff4271bc5be1136bf17e4e5b291b01033d608db
Signed-off-by: Peter Portante <peter.portante@redhat.com>

commit_message:
Fix test to work with mock 0.8.0

This particular test case used a construct that worked in mock 1.0,
but not in 0.8. Our test-requirements.txt says mock>=0.8.0.

Change-Id: I93ed4b7b5d169572bbed6490cb9b0dd421a3b9e2

commit_message:
Linux device name can have '@' or ':' characters

It's possible to set '@' or ':' character in Linux device name. But
Neutron IP lib doesn't handle correctly these names.

To distinguish VLAN devices from others devices with '@' in their name,
the details option in iproute2 is used.

Change-Id: I7ed24ec00f481207d97bdef052f86388f24d9b21
Closes-Bug: #1245799

commit_message:
GlusterFS: Synchronize operations that manipulate qcow2 data

Operations that modify qcow2 chains or the GlusterFS driver's
snapshot info file should use locking so that more than one thread
cannot run these operations at the same time.

Without this it is possible for multiple threads to concurrently
modify snapshot information resulting in an incomplete snapshot
chain.

Closes-Bug: #1251425

Change-Id: I93c6ffecd9aec38560cb19085243390b9120b363

commit_message:
Fixes Hyper-V Inspector disk metrics bug

Changed disk metric names used by Hyper-V utils.

Was using wrong metric names before. 'Aggregated Disk Data Read/Written'
metrics refers to all disks (sum), while the metrics needs to be per disk.

Change-Id: I4ec36152a8b8147069151dd6eb98f36f7aab9229
Closes-Bug: 1250336

commit_message:
Make compute manager _init_instance use native objects

Actually, it already did, but it was still using old interfaces
for making updates. This just cleans that up along with the
associated tests.

Related to blueprint compute-manager-objects

Change-Id: I1f0f9894f3003133eade712c965155f8516e5225

(2 inline comments)

Found one exception message that should be updated for consistency with the format of other exceptions while we are changing this code.

Also a question for clarification.  I am surprised that all the driver specific exceptions are being left at the end of the file.  Had expected that you were going to try and get them to conform to one of the three classes.  Is the idea that any exceptions that are likely to rise up to the volume manager during run time need to inherit from the classes and the exceptions that are left are specific to the configuration and initialization of each driver.  I think that is implied based on looking at the types of exceptions in the file, but wanted to better understand that.  If so, what can we do to enforce proper usage of exceptions.  Just going to have to make sure that the core reviewers are all on the same page with regards to exception definition and usage?"}, {'account_id': 4355, 'date': '2013-11-12 07:30:36.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Good start!  A few things, which don't necessarily need to go into this patch:

1. Should we move driver-specific exceptions out of exceptions.py?

2. Should we have more high-level exception classes to indicate rescheduling?  For example, if we're creating a volume from an image and Glance isn't responding or the image is corrupt, don't reschedule.  If it's a back-end issue on the other hand, do reschedule.  I'm not sure what other cases fall under this category.

3. Update the rescheduling blacklist/whitelist?"}, {'account_id': 2243, 'date': '2013-11-12 15:30:47.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-11-12 16:05:26.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: Doesn't seem to work

commit_message:
Subclass vendor specific exceptions.

Up until now drivers have been able to define their
own custom exception classes.  In most cases these are
inherited from either a native python exception class
or at best the base cinder exception class.

The problem with this is that it makes it very difficult
for higher layers (such as volume manager) to do any intelligent
exception handling and the base Cinder.exception class is too broad.

This change takes the first step in cleaning this up.  We create
new exception classes for all drivers to inherit from:
  VolumeDriverException
  VolumeBackendAPIException
  BackupDriverException

This still allows the freedom to create custom exceptions for a
particular driver, however it also gives us a common exception
class to catch and check in higher levels.  Further refinement
and standardization will be helpful going forward but this
should give us a good start.

Change-Id: I8c2ca4eecf7a64a82846d6d24fc0239db086237e

commit_message:
upload_image.sh should handle file URLs

upload_image.sh doesn't handle correctly file URLs: a file URL works only
if the file is already in the cache.
This patch provides support for file URLs of local files (RFC 1738)
http://tools.ietf.org/html/rfc1738

Change-Id: I107299c543cfa189e32848c32eefdbeb51a5e1f5
Closes-Bug: #1251752

commit_message:
Refactor UnexpectedTaskStateError for handling of deleting instances

To avoid having to repeatedly unfold UnexpectedTaskStateErrors and
do seperate handling of the 'deleting' task state from other states,
everywhere this exception is handled, introduce a separate exception
UnexpectedDeletingTaskStateError that derives from the above.

This way, most handling of InstanceNotFound to handle instances gone
during some action can be made to also include this new exception.

Change-Id: Ia833c2b2361f32c7e33c84ec14d3af6231119a99
Related-Bug: #1223843

commit_message:
Avoid reset of repeat_actions attribute on alarm update

Fixes bug 1253057

Previously, when an unrelated alarm attribute was updated via the CLI,
the repeat_actions attribute was also set to False as an unwanted side-effect.

Now, we only set this attribute in the update call if explicitly specified
as a CLI arg. Otherwise the value provided in the PUT request body reflects
the pre-existing value for this attribute.

Change-Id: I94468ff649dd4367848c74e94a3feb08494bb223

[{'created': '2013-11-21 06:37:01.000000000', 'message': 'Fix disagreement percentage calculation

Previously, a disagreement was defined as a core reviewer giving a
negative vote after the person had given a positive vote.  The
percentage was then the number of disagreements / all positive votes.

Later, disagreements were extended to cover the opposite case: when a
core member gives a positive vote after a person had given a negative
vote.

The percentage calculation was not updated to reflect this new
definition.  It still showed disagreements as a percentage of the
positive votes, instead of all of them (+ and -).

Change-Id: I6392055e5d95dfece86cdd427f44e258566e771a
'}]
commit_message:
Fix disagreement percentage calculation

Previously, a disagreement was defined as a core reviewer giving a
negative vote after the person had given a positive vote.  The
percentage was then the number of disagreements / all positive votes.

Later, disagreements were extended to cover the opposite case: when a
core member gives a positive vote after a person had given a negative
vote.

The percentage calculation was not updated to reflect this new
definition.  It still showed disagreements as a percentage of the
positive votes, instead of all of them (+ and -).

Change-Id: I6392055e5d95dfece86cdd427f44e258566e771a

commit_message:
Fix cells instance_create extra kwarg

When the API cell receives a message to update an instance, it'll try to
create it if it doesn't already exist in order to sync up.  However,
it's calling db.instance_create with an extra kwarg that doesn't exist
and failing.  This patch removes the extra kwarg.

The bug was introduced in this change id:

Ife5be9922db0742c8ee4f970517396be86597cce

Change-Id: I69bcb3dda2cbb566b0d69c5eac005703654ea811
Closes-bug: 1247919

Any quarantines and errors that happened between the last recon dump
and the end of an audit pass weren't getting counted in the logs.

This is particularly easy to see on a mostly-empty SAIO: go corrupt a
file, and the auditor will probably tell you (a) that it's

commit_message:
Fix quarantine, error counts in audit logs

Any quarantines and errors that happened between the last recon dump
and the end of an audit pass weren't getting counted in the logs.

This is particularly easy to see on a mostly-empty SAIO: go corrupt a
file, and the auditor will probably tell you (a) that it's
quarantining a file, and then (b) that 0 files were quarantined.

Change-Id: I78e32b911e457078144564e3be42527260148ade

commit_message:
Allow users to configure the CM pipeline interval

The patch allows users to configure the ceilometer pipeline interval.
In localrc, we can add CEILOMETER_PIPELINE_INTERVAL=10 to handle the
pipeline each 10 seconds instead of the default 10 minutes.

Change-Id: Ic5216adbdfd70ade38912871ac6df3be732bf780

Trying to understand whether this is something CM ought to change this or Oslo.

Why not change this in Oslo to make the concept of max_retries for RPC more generic, like 'amqp_max_retries' and put it in openstack.common.rpc.amqp module? Is RabbitMQ the only queueing scheme that would make use of a max retry setting?

I see a maximum number of connection attempts as being a broader concept that each implementation could use, especially for generic local RPC modules for each project."}, {'account_id': 1812, 'date': '2013-10-25 15:59:48.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: (2 inline comments)

'}, {'account_id': 2284, 'date': '2013-10-25 16:00:29.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

@thomasm: sure, I agree that olso is probably the appropriate place for this kind of logic in the long-term.

However the intent here is just to address the immediate issue in self-contained, low-risk way that's suitable for cherry-picking onto stable/havana and being picked up from there by distros.

Cheers,
Eoghan"}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-10-25 16:01:56.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Works for me

'}, {'account_id': 1669, 'date': '2013-10-25 18:06:45.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

Definitely not a good fix to special case drivers.

If a publisher fails to load and is not used in the pipeline, then Ceilometer should continue to work."}, {'account_id': 2284, 'date': '2013-10-26 11:14:08.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

@jd__: thanks for the review.

> Definitely not a good fix to special case drivers.

Yes, I'd prefer not to have any driver-specific code in this class, but what's there currently is rabbitmq-specific code being hit *regardless* of which RPC driver is configured.

So at least having this driver-specific code being restricted to the special case where the corresponding driver has been configured is a step forward IMO.

It would be preferable certainly to have the ability to suppress the driver-specific retry logic in a generic way, but I think this would require some changes in the oslo RPC code. That would be more intrusive and not easy to get onto stable/havana or into dristos that consume from the stable branch.

> If a publisher fails to load and is not used in the pipeline, then Ceilometer should continue to work.

The problem here is that only the rpc:// driver is configured out-of-the-box in the pipeline.yaml - so if this single publisher fails to load, then all bets are off.

Sure, the rest of ceilometer continues to gather samples etc, but that's kind of useless AFAICS since these data can't be published without a working publisher terminating the pipeline.

Cheers,
Eoghan"}, {'account_id': 1669, 'date': '2013-10-28 10:21:30.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

I see what you mean here, I've read the patch a little too fast so I miss a bit of context indeed.

I think I agree with Thomas about this should be fixed in Oslo, so I stand on my -1! :-)"}, {'account_id': 9, 'date': '2013-11-05 06:03:11.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Abandoned

@jd__: I appreciate the idea that thomasm is advocating, however the intent here is simply to address the immediate issue in self-contained, low-risk way that's suitable for cherry-picking onto stable/havana and being picked up from there by distros.

Making corresponding changes to oslo that could be required by the ceilometer fix would make consuming the fix as intended much more awkward.

For obvious reasons, I really want to minimize the number of distro-specific patches being carried, and getting a fix for this issue with minimal blast-radius landed upstream would help towards that goal.

Cheers,
Eoghan"}, {'account_id': 1669, 'date': '2013-11-20 12:43:39.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Approved

commit_message:
Selectively import RPC backend retry config

Fixes bug 1244698

When setting the RPC publisher policies, selectively import
the retry config native to the configured RPC backend.

This avoid ImportErrors when all the dependencies of an unused
RPC backend are not installed locally.

Change-Id: If05a5a389a1b417875e0426fd83fb6d73d570487

commit_message:
Use correct device_manager member in dhcp driver

* The DHCP driver used to use device_delegate, but that has
  changed to device_manager. referencing device_delegate
  caused the cleanup of the dhcp agent namespaces to fail.
  This fixes the issue by using the correct member name,
  device_manager

Change-Id: Iab8ea0549383335ff66f3f13df1953d206eeb28f
Closes-Bug: #1245408

commit_message:
Support a new qpid topology

There has been a bug open for a while pointing out that the way we
create direct exchanges with qpid results in leaking exchanges since
qpid doesn't support auto-deleting exchanges.  This was somewhat
mitigated by change to use a single reply queue.  This meant we created
far fewer direct exchanges, but the problem persists anyway.

A Qpid expert, William Henry, originally proposed a change to address
this issue.  Unfortunately, it wasn't backwards compatible with existing
installations.  This patch takes the same approach, but makes it
optional and off by default.  This will allow a migration period.

As a really nice side effect, the Qpid experts have told us that this
change will also allow us to use Qpid broker federation to provide HA.

DocImpact
Closes-bug: #1178375
Co-authored-by: William Henry <whenry@redhat.com>
Change-Id: I09b8317c0d8a298237beeb3105f2b90cb13933d8

commit_message:
Move flags in powervm/driver into a powervm option group

This change moves powervm specific flags into a new "powervm"
options group.

DocImpact: the following flags have been moved to this group (I
have dropped the powervm_ prefix from the flags at the same time):
    powervm_mgr_type (renamed manager_type)
    powervm_mgr (renamed manager_host)
    powervm_mgr_user (renamed manager_user)
    powervm_mgr_passwd (renamed manager_password)
    powervm_img_remote_path
    powervm_img_local_path

Implements blueprint: powervm-opts-group

Change-Id: Ie896b00a2813c219661f662166a7987d24de4400

@Jamie Lennox: You should've added negative feedback describing your concerns on my original patch, then it wouldn't have been merged - IIRC I did ask you to do exactly that on Wednesday..

I'd still like to understand the details of your concerns, and why the tests are failing - is it just that some tests expect the current behavior (i.e they look for the stale token instead of the current one?)

I understand why the revert, but I'm still not clear what the next step is - we (Heat) need to be able to re-scope a token to a trust without forcing users to use username/password auth, and I still think that enforcing token immutability in the client is wrong, since it's not a feature of the underlying API."}, {'account_id': 2218, 'date': '2013-11-21 13:53:31.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Looks good to me (core reviewer); Approved

'}, {'account_id': 7725, 'date': '2013-11-21 14:00:08.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

@shardy I don't think that the tests expect an expired token.  The code expects that when it sets a new auth token that it will be used: http://bit.ly/I1sRz2.

The naive fix is to set `self.auth_ref = None` from the `auth_token` setter, but I doubt that this is the right fix.

Since I am new to this area it would really help me out to see a broken test that shows the behavior you expect to see. If I have something like that I'll be more able to help come up with a solution."}, {'account_id': 6486, 'date': '2013-11-21 14:00:20.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

@Steve - this was resubmitted as https://review.openstack.org/#/c/57585/

To make it a little easier to test with a local keystoneclient, I submitted this: https://review.openstack.org/#/c/57586/ , so you could check it out and run the keystone tests yourself and to see the errors. The problem might be in Keystone's keystoneclient tests and not in this change. commit_message:
Revert "Merge "Avoid returning stale token via auth_token property""

This reverts commit b89d28663ed181e1df56ada271931891a4c77f67, reversing
changes made to 8a0732e262cd9de508399eabeb705b681c2503c0.

This change was causing gate issues. It breaks a few Keystone tests in
test_keystoneclient.py.

Change-Id: I8de6988c554a1359c04ce2d1a8c4707dee7c3782

commit_message:
Remove unused method setup_logging

Method setup_logging in glance/common/config.py wasn't used anywhere.
Similar function is in oslo, and some modules in Glance are using
function log.setup from oslo, like glance/cmd/manage.py#L123

Closes-Bug: #1248214

Change-Id: Icda26943f02df5e495179868aa8b1f4c4e151803
(cherry picked from commit 66f52c0b0d03362b72f65631af3e562cc999f84a)

logging config when a API call failure was encountered

commit_message:
Ensure basic logging config is applied

Fixes bug 1252775

Previously the CLI emitted an obscure message related to
logging config when a API call failure was encountered
without the --debug flag being set:

  No handlers could be found for logger "ceilometerclient.common.http"

Now we always set the basic logging config with serverity
level of warning at least, so as to give the user a more
friendly and less confusing error message.

Change-Id: I5c6e70e97defca49ca62346f90190935646ff383

commit_message:
Fixes image delete and upload contention

If an image upload completes during a delete on the same
image, the image data may not be deleted. This patch
resolves this issue and provides a unit test to test it.

Co-authored-by: Hirofumi Ichihara <ichihara.hirofumi@lab.ntt.co.jp>
Change-Id: I913cd3e4963b7b60da6a856eb820c1afcc9017d7
Fixes: bug 1245099

[{'created': '2013-11-19 03:03:37.000000000', 'message': "Shows 'last_error' property for a node

https://review.openstack.org/#/c/54466/ introduced a 'last_error'
field for a node. This string field is used to store the last error
from any requested asynchronous operation (eg, whether that was to
change power state, or deploy a node, or anything else) that
started but failed to finish. It is cleared when any new asynchronous
operation is started.

With this change, an 'ironic node-show' command will also return the
'last_error' value (if any) for the specified node.

Change-Id: I9663662a1a1237cc356e17947aa86b0bf0954339
"}]
commit_message:
Shows 'last_error' property for a node

https://review.openstack.org/#/c/54466/ introduced a 'last_error'
field for a node. This string field is used to store the last error
from any requested asynchronous operation (eg, whether that was to
change power state, or deploy a node, or anything else) that
started but failed to finish. It is cleared when any new asynchronous
operation is started.

With this change, an 'ironic node-show' command will also return the
'last_error' value (if any) for the specified node.

Change-Id: I9663662a1a1237cc356e17947aa86b0bf0954339

Rename parameters

commit_message:
Conditionalise automatic enabling of disabled host

The change Ib8d67838ceb73c5b1cdc9498c17b335e9e5bb6f3 introduced
automatic behaviour to the nova-compute hosts, which will now
automatically disable themselves if they lose contact with libvirtd,
and re-endable themselves on a successful reconnection.

However, this tramples over any operational service disablement
that may be in place (on an otherwise working host) for any number
of good reasons.

As suggested in bug #1250049, this is a quick fix which attaches
a prefix to any host disable_reason string, and only re-enables
a host if that string is still present.

Fixes-bug: #1250049
Change-Id: Ia7544a357d1385db5fa92e500cb691f49436cfc9

commit_message:
Add last_error usage to deploy and teardown methods

Change I7e079627b87b2cb1606e677e287dd08dcc87263a introduce new
'last_error' field in nodes table. This patch add saving error
messages in this field for do_node_deploy and do_node_tear_down
methods of conductor.

Change-Id: I9aaab42c1e91568ab6a4657df4fe972441e3ac6d

commit_message:
User-Create Host Does Not Allow Wildcarded Octet

as of now, the only wildcarding pattern that will succeed for
user-create's 'host' parameter is '%'.

this patch permits wildcarded octets, e.g. '10.%' & '192.168.1.%'

Change-Id: If58ee69381d1bbf3be4af37c045d6f8a2d924947
Closes-Bug: 1245705

commit_message:
Add missing argument max_size in libvirt driver

max_size argument was added in commit 3cdfe894ab58f7b91bf7fb690fc5bc724e44066f,
but missing  in _create_ephemeral and _create_swap method, which cause
exception raised when caching ephemeral and swap disk files of the instance.

Add test for _create_ephemeral used with max_size parameter
and test _create_swap method

Change-Id: I46032ad32f317c923692b8b3d40cedd0dce06cad
Closes-Bug: 1251152
Closes-Bug: 1250032

revisions:
[{'created': '2013-10-23 22:58:09.000000000', 'message': 'xenapi: kernel and ramdisk missing after live-migrate

After a live migration is performed with xenserver, the kernel
and ramdisk images are not moved to destination.  This means:
* need to manually add them to the destination host
* need to manually clean them on source host

Adding the images is fairly straightforward by calling
create_kernel_and_ramdisk at post_live_migration_at_destination.
Removing images requires us to cache image ids as they are
taken from VM record which is deleted by the time the post
operation comes along.  We use the migrate_data to cache the
image data for removal.

The unit tests are adjusted to handle new calls for existing
tests.

Fixes bug 1224561

Change-Id: I741398db9ddb6764408878a11cf4c80544bbc901

commit_message:
xenapi: kernel and ramdisk missing after live-migrate

After a live migration is performed with xenserver, the kernel
and ramdisk images are not moved to destination.  This means:
* need to manually add them to the destination host
* need to manually clean them on source host

Adding the images is fairly straightforward by calling
create_kernel_and_ramdisk at post_live_migration_at_destination.
Removing images requires us to cache image ids as they are
taken from VM record which is deleted by the time the post
operation comes along.  We use the migrate_data to cache the
image data for removal.

The unit tests are adjusted to handle new calls for existing
tests.

Fixes bug 1224561

Change-Id: I741398db9ddb6764408878a11cf4c80544bbc901

commit_message:
LVM: Activate source LV before cloning from it

LVM may be configured to not automatically activate
thin-provisioned LVs.

Ensure they are activated when performing a clone, otherwise
dd will fail as the device does not exist in /dev/mapper/.

Closes-Bug: #1252423

Change-Id: Ibcb946ffe7804b1976bf1b1863c48340c8cc7fd5

commit_message:
Add missing ConfigNotFound exception

ConfigNotFound is raised as an exception from ironic.common.policy.py
if the policy file does not exist, yet the exception was not defined
in ironic.common.exception.py

Change-Id: Ic900c31c4fcad1ec27c54ab45af482293b51215c

commit_message:
libvirt: pass instance to a log() call in the standard way

If we pass the instance in the correct way, then we get nicely
formatted logs which are easier for admins to use.

Change-Id: I27ab372a3388e2aa02491da07c616807bcbb14ef

commit_message:
Move flags in libvirt's imagecache to the libvirt group

This change continues moving libvirt specific flags into a libvirt
specific configuration group.

Progresses blueprint libvirt-opts-group.

DocImpact: the following flags move into the libvirt group:
image_info_filename_pattern, remove_unused_base_images,
remove_unused_kernels, remove_unused_resized_minimum_age_seconds,
remove_unused_original_minimum_age_seconds, checksum_base_images,
checksum_interval_seconds.

Change-Id: Iea681c7db7efc9da0525ef8e01b4900ca71f10cf

commit_message:
Move base_dir_name option to somewhere more central

The VMWare hypervisor driver is using the base_dir_name flag, but
it was defined in the libvirt driver. Given I am moving flags for
libvirt into a libvirt group, this flag needs to move somewhere
more central. It has also been renamed to the more descriptive
image_cache_subdirectory_name.

Progresses blueprint libvirt-opts-group.

DocImpact: the base_dir_name flag has been renamed
image_cache_subdirectory_name, although the old name will continue
to work for the forseeable future.

Change-Id: If016456b9f571ff0ec88621bd17e463faeef95ba

subject: Move some libvirt specific flags into a group

[{'created': '2013-11-07 06:12:28.000000000', 'message': 'Move some libvirt specific flags into a group

This is backwards compatible via deprecated groups. This change
moves the flags defined in nova/virt/libvirt/driver.py into a
"libvirt" configuration group.

There are other flags which need to be moved, but this change
is quite large, so I will handle those in follow up changes.

Progresses blueprint libvirt-opts-group.

DocImpact: the following flags are moved into a "libvirt" flag
group: rescue_image_id, rescue_kernel_id, rescue_ramdisk_id,
libvirt_type, libvirt_uri, libvirt_inject_password,
libvirt_inject_key, libvirt_inject_partition, use_usb_tablet,
live_migration_uri, live_migration_flag, block_migration_flag,
live_migration_bandwidth, snapshot_image_format,
libvirt_vif_driver, libvirt_volume_drivers

Change-Id: I11e79eb5fd79c459374b9bf04707a4e6d79e993f
'}, {'created': '2013-11-07 14:58:58.000000000', 'message': 'Move some libvirt specific flags into a group

This is backwards compatible via deprecated groups. This change
moves the flags defined in nova/virt/libvirt/driver.py into a
"libvirt" configuration group.

There are other flags which need to be moved, but this change
is quite large, so I will handle those in follow up changes.

Now that the flags in nova/virt/libvirt/driver.py are in a libvirt
group, we can drop the libvirt_ from in front of many of the flag
names as well.

Progresses blueprint libvirt-opts-group.

DocImpact: the following flags are moved into a "libvirt" flag
group: rescue_image_id, rescue_kernel_id, rescue_ramdisk_id,
libvirt_type, libvirt_uri, libvirt_inject_password,
libvirt_inject_key, libvirt_inject_partition, use_usb_tablet,
live_migration_uri, live_migration_flag, block_migration_flag,
live_migration_bandwidth, snapshot_image_format,
libvirt_vif_driver, libvirt_volume_drivers

The following flags have had the libvirt_ dropped from the start of
their flag name now that they are in a flag group:
    libvirt_type (now conn_type)
    libvirt_uri (now conn_uri)
    libvirt_inject_password
    libvirt_inject_key
    libvirt_inject_partition
    libvirt_vif_driver
    libvirt_volume_drivers
    libvirt_disk_prefix
    libvirt_wait_soft_reboot_seconds
    libvirt_non_blocking
    libvirt_cpu_mode
    libvirt_cpu_model
    libvirt_snapshots_directory

Finally, the flag libvirt.nonblocking has been renamed to
libvirt.api_thread_pool, which is more descriptive.

Change-Id: I11e79eb5fd79c459374b9bf04707a4e6d79e993f
'}, {'created': '2013-11-08 23:54:17.000000000', 'message': 'Move some libvirt specific flags into a group

This is backwards compatible via deprecated groups. This change
moves the flags defined in nova/virt/libvirt/driver.py into a
"libvirt" configuration group.

There are other flags which need to be moved, but this change
is quite large, so I will handle those in follow up changes.

Now that the flags in nova/virt/libvirt/driver.py are in a libvirt
group, we can drop the libvirt_ from in front of many of the flag
names as well.

Progresses blueprint libvirt-opts-group.

DocImpact: the following flags are moved into a "libvirt" flag
group: rescue_image_id, rescue_kernel_id, rescue_ramdisk_id,
libvirt_type, libvirt_uri, libvirt_inject_password,
libvirt_inject_key, libvirt_inject_partition, use_usb_tablet,
live_migration_uri, live_migration_flag, block_migration_flag,
live_migration_bandwidth, snapshot_image_format,
libvirt_vif_driver, libvirt_volume_drivers

The following flags have had the libvirt_ dropped from the start of
their flag name now that they are in a flag group:
    libvirt_type (now driver_type)
    libvirt_uri (now conn_uri)
    libvirt_inject_password
    libvirt_inject_key
    libvirt_inject_partition
    libvirt_vif_driver
    libvirt_volume_drivers
    libvirt_disk_prefix
    libvirt_wait_soft_reboot_seconds
    libvirt_non_blocking
    libvirt_cpu_mode
    libvirt_cpu_model
    libvirt_snapshots_directory

Finally, the flag libvirt.nonblocking has been renamed to

commit_message:
Move some libvirt specific flags into a group

This is backwards compatible via deprecated groups. This change
moves the flags defined in nova/virt/libvirt/driver.py into a
"libvirt" configuration group.

There are other flags which need to be moved, but this change
is quite large, so I will handle those in follow up changes.

Now that the flags in nova/virt/libvirt/driver.py are in a libvirt
group, we can drop the libvirt_ from in front of many of the flag
names as well.

Progresses blueprint libvirt-opts-group.

DocImpact: the following flags are moved into a "libvirt" flag
group: rescue_image_id, rescue_kernel_id, rescue_ramdisk_id,
libvirt_type, libvirt_uri, libvirt_inject_password,
libvirt_inject_key, libvirt_inject_partition, use_usb_tablet,
live_migration_uri, live_migration_flag, block_migration_flag,
live_migration_bandwidth, snapshot_image_format,
libvirt_vif_driver, libvirt_volume_drivers

The following flags have had the libvirt_ dropped from the start of
their flag name now that they are in a flag group:
    libvirt_type (now virt_type)
    libvirt_uri (now conn_uri)
    libvirt_inject_password
    libvirt_inject_key
    libvirt_inject_partition
    libvirt_vif_driver
    libvirt_volume_drivers
    libvirt_disk_prefix
    libvirt_wait_soft_reboot_seconds
    libvirt_non_blocking
    libvirt_cpu_mode
    libvirt_cpu_model
    libvirt_snapshots_directory

The name for the virt_type flag was influenced by bug 1195361,
which shows confusion as to what the flag is setting (the
virtualization type libvirt uses, not the driver libvirt uses
to achieve that).

Finally, the flag libvirt.nonblocking has been renamed to
libvirt.api_thread_pool, which is more descriptive.

Change-Id: I11e79eb5fd79c459374b9bf04707a4e6d79e993f

commit_message:
Initial KDS service

The Key Distribution Service is used to register keys for services and
distribute tickets to contact othe services.

The KDS is used to digitally sign and optionally encrypt messages sent over the
message queue by the rpc modules.

It implements the service described in this document:
https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/MessageSecurity#A_Key_Distribution_Server_in_Keystone

DocImpact
SecurityImpact
blueprint key-distribution-server
Change-Id: Ib47aca8f72623a07ff18f23d46d0af520e463fc9
Co-Authored-By: Jamie Lennox <jamielennox@redhat.com>

Man, I really hate rolling our own shell sanitizing function.  There isn't some widely used and well-tested library we could use to do this instead?"}, {'account_id': 5046, 'date': '2013-07-09 13:49:55.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

Hey Ben, thanks for the review. I agree and there is a subprocess module that handles this. It is implemented in other parts of Nova. However we are using Paramiko to send commands to a remote system. 

http://docs.python.org/2/library/subprocess.html#using-the-subprocess-module'}, {'account_id': 6928, 'date': '2013-07-09 14:33:31.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: No score

Hate is such a strong word.  Apparently I was feeling dramatic yesterday. :-)

Anyway, I'm still not crazy about rolling our own sanitizer.  I was thinking of something like this: http://docs.python.org/dev/library/shlex.html#shlex.quote but the status of that function in Python 2 is a little weird.  According to the docs (http://docs.python.org/2/library/pipes.html#pipes.quote) it's deprecated, but I don't feel like you normally bother renaming functions that are actually deprecated (unless the renaming is the reason for the deprecation, which it isn't in this case).

Either way, this is definitely an improvement over what was there before so I'll take back my -1, but I would like to hear some other thoughts on using quote instead."}, {'account_id': 6873, 'date': '2013-07-09 14:50:05.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

Lance, I think you mentioned that the bug tracking this also impacts cinder and maybe some other projects. Are there reviews up for those?  How do others plan on handling this?'}, {'account_id': 5046, 'date': '2013-07-09 15:08:34.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

Matt, other projects are being hardened depending on the case and who owns them: 

https://review.openstack.org/#/c/34580/
https://bugs.launchpad.net/nova/+bug/1074087

I am taking responsibility for the PowerVM case and this change is designed to touch only that. Given that this is a potential problem with security and could be case by case, it makes sense to me to keep the patches in a case by case basis.

Ben, thanks for the links. I'll look into it. I am hesitant on the fact that it is deprecated but I'm still curious :)

Thanks guys!"}, {'account_id': 4393, 'date': '2013-07-10 21:15:57.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

I'm not sure whether that's something that needs to happen for this change, or if it should just get moved later."}, {'account_id': 5046, 'date': '2013-07-15 17:48:50.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: (1 inline comment)

Thanks for the review Ben, I responded inline. On the Oslo part of the question, I guess it would be helpful if someone from Oslo had an opinion on that. I can purpose to Oslo if that is wanted, but most other cases people are using subprocess.popen to address this issue instead or a roll your own sanitizer.'}, {'account_id': 6928, 'date': '2013-07-15 19:01:50.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3: (1 inline comment)

Response inline.  I guess basically I'd like to see a test case for the single quote case, even if it does work as-is.

Regarding Oslo, I'm okay with this going in here, but I do think it eventually belongs there.  Even if there's nothing else doing this sort of thing (and I see other uses of paramiko in OpenStack, so I think there is), there could be in the future and they will all need this code.

However, I know markmc has said that he prefers code to go into a project first and then get moved to Oslo, so that's something we can revisit later."}, {'account_id': 5046, 'date': '2013-07-15 19:16:13.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 4.'}, {'account_id': 5046, 'date': '2013-07-15 19:16:44.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

A typo nit and a comment inline.

One other thought I'm having as I look through this is that right now there's nothing to ensure we aren't calling run_vios_command with a raw command that hasn't been sanitized.  I'm not sure I would want to hold up a security fix for that, but I think it would be good if the sanitization could be either integrated into run_vios_command or maybe we somehow tag a command as safe (even something as simple as sticking a prefix on it that run_vios_command can look for and strip off again).  I mean, hopefully that sort of thing would get caught in review anyway, but mistakes do happen. :-)"}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-07-15 20:42:54.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5: Works for me

Harking back to Ben' s comment [[
One other thought I'm having as I look through this is that right now there's nothing to ensure we aren't calling run_vios_command with a raw command that hasn't been sanitized. I'm not sure I would want to hold up a security fix for that, but I think it would be good if the sanitization could be either integrated into run_vios_command or maybe we somehow tag a command as safe (even something as simple as sticking a prefix on it that run_vios_command can look for and strip off again). I mean, hopefully that sort of thing would get caught in review anyway, but mistakes do happen. :-)]] and mine own mis-givings in this direction
1) better if run-vios-cmd run command_checker on any command it is given, that ensures invoked "safely"
2) this would essentially be snip off the first string with no spaces (the command) which leaves only the arguments, and your code to check for special characters works on each of the arguments, one or more of them.
3) Did not see any response to the comment about the pipe character.
4) Would we want to have a list of acceptable commands, as part of Command class init routine for all command invocations in a component. That is an extra fail safe mechanism, protecting from user error. Like a whitelist of commands?
ldbragst == must be tedious to deal with all the comments, but this just may go into Oslo, so the stronger it is, the better.
Regards
Malini'}, {'account_id': 5046, 'date': '2013-08-23 12:56:28.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 12.'}, {'account_id': 6928, 'date': '2013-08-23 12:56:50.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 12: Looks good to me, but someone else must approve

commit_message:
Address security concerns in PowerVM Driver

Add two methods to common.py that will help check commands
being sent to the remote VIOS system to prevent shell injection.

fixes bug 1192971

[SecurityImpact]

Change-Id: If5ac48c5c889034c7b0ba24d977e8f4a14137a12

commit_message:
Make heat depend on python-heatclient

This will be required soon for one or more of the
following reasons:
* Multi-region invoking stacks on other heat endpoints
* A variant of nested stack which goes through API instead of
  internally
* Orchestrating new heat-based resources (autoscaling, software config)
* Possibly sharing some template parsing and validation between
  client and server by moving this code to client

revisions:
[{'created': '2013-11-12 18:10:11.000000000', 'message': "Fix probe test

Fix for a probe test that failed every once in a
while due to the early-majority change previously
committed. Sometimes a write would return success
before the third node had succeeded and the probe
test would look for on-disk evidence and fail,
when it would've been fine had it waited just a
bit longer for the third node to complete.

Since there's no real way for the probe test to
know when all three nodes are done, I just made
it retry once a second for several seconds before
reporting an error.

There may be more tests like this we'll have to
fix as we run across them.

Change-Id: I749e43d4580a7c726a9a8648f71bafefa70a05f5
"}]
commit_message:
Fix probe test

Fix for a probe test that failed every once in a
while due to the early-majority change previously
committed. Sometimes a write would return success
before the third node had succeeded and the probe
test would look for on-disk evidence and fail,
when it would've been fine had it waited just a
bit longer for the third node to complete.

Since there's no real way for the probe test to
know when all three nodes are done, I just made
it retry once a second for several seconds before
reporting an error.

There may be more tests like this we'll have to
fix as we run across them.

Change-Id: I749e43d4580a7c726a9a8648f71bafefa70a05f5

commit_message:
Enable/disable ironic in tempest config

In order to run tempest tests for Ironic in devstack
the availability of the Ironic service must be set in
the tempest config.

This patch adds a shortcut for Ironic services and sets
availability of Ironic in tempest config.

Change-Id: I206fc2ea13412ceb128f8bfe90c153348d6f2f3e

commit_message:
Skip test_create_backup

test_get_console_output fails many times now.
test_create_backup is a previous test of test_get_console_output, and
test_create_backup has been merged since 2013/11/15. The date is when
this failure started to happen.

But this is just a inference. However, after much checking the problem
seems to go away with this change.

Change-Id: I7fbdcec6c7990d7a9822037782729814cc6b6b79

commit_message:
Remove radmin credentials from create_heat_client

auth_token is enough for authentication
in creating a heatclient.Client instance.

Currently both username/password and auth_token
are passed as argument in create_heat_client

Fixes: Bug 1251203

Change-Id: I3cce6b35fc40f4ff4cc45b04714067956fb1869d

The new CLI allows for Rax auth, but alas it does not work the same way
as the old CLI did. This means that any scripts using both have to have
their auth URLs switched.

The fix for this is to include a new auth type for the old CLI tool

'}]
commit_message:
Allow for compatable auths between new and old CLI

The new CLI allows for Rax auth, but alas it does not work the same way
as the old CLI did. This means that any scripts using both have to have
their auth URLs switched.

The fix for this is to include a new auth type for the old CLI tool
that adds "/tokens" to the auth URL the way the new CLI does.

Fixes bug 1253746

Change-Id: I5705d87033cc42b9dfa136ca13e4e5ab83bd666d

commit_message:
Remove confusing message about mysql credentials

The Glance installation material contained a note indicating that if
connecting to MySQL fails the user should use the IP address of the
database server instead when specifying the credentials.

Besides being confusing in its wording this note referred to a situation
that the user could not possibly become aware of until starting the
Glance services later in the chapter.

Additionally no such warning is included elsewhere in the guide as its
presumed (via specification in the prerequisites up front) that the user
has set up their /etc/hosts files such that the controller host name will
resolve.

Change-Id: Ic5e6e1820628b0854effe7594b09610d030d0573
Closes-Bug: #1251458
backport:havana
(cherry picked from commit 426429b109d6b946745f3c15de949e59050ba5c1)

commit_message:
Cleans up marconi-queues and marconi-proxy config files

Changes [proxy:config] and [queues:config] into
just [drivers] since both these projects are
separate and so there's less repetition.

Change-Id: I1d198111042ba4bdcff78c6ae6fbe087b2fe01e6
Closes-Bug:#1231669

commit_message:
Set LIBVIRT_DEFAULT_URI in .bashrc

If LIBVIRT_DEFAULT_URI is not set on login then the virtual power
manager may not be able to find the instances it is supposed to
manage.

Change-Id: I39540f785f5cb89879e25cc5928d9a580c69dc7b

commit_message:
Add ML2 plugin support

This patch aims to support:
- ml2 configuration for Open-vSwitch & Linux Bridge plugins
- mechanism drivers: flat, gre, vlan vxlan
- l2 population support for OVS & linux bridge plugins

implement blueprint ml2-support
Change-Id: I9a4224f899e95411c509f583bf04dfc4dd0de25b
Signed-off-by: Emilien Macchi <emilien.macchi@enovance.com>

commit_message:
Don't use deprecated module commands

The commands module was deprecated since version 2.6 and it has been
removed in Python 3. This patch uses processutils.trycmd method to
replace of deprecated module commands.
See http://docs.python.org/2/library/commands#module-commands

Closes-Bug: #1248216

Change-Id: Iee0b3cf59c738bfda9c5b2049a1853abbb6d16e0

commit_message:
Improve error reporting on import failures

The existing config generator code does not report general errors
importing modules well.  In my case, that meant I had no idea that
an old version of six on my system was causing a module import to
fail.

This change logs all errors importing a module to stderr.

Change-Id: I4663f5bbd4f553c0d6ce5f84b1c1275a7304e3b5

an empty module name if extra modules were not specified.  This

env var won't cause problems.

commit_message:
Clean up extra modules code

The config generator extra modules code was attempting to look up
an empty module name if extra modules were not specified.  This
resulted in a spurious exception.

This change also strips the module names so extra spaces in the
env var won't cause problems.

Change-Id: I4cfbeb62fc25220ab43d6f80006245be3376dc93

commit_message:
Refactor reset-db so we don't sync by default.

Now that we call db sync in post configure for each service
we no longer need to do it here.

Refactors the reset-db script so that we don't call DB sync's by
default. We still support the ability to db sync with reset-db
by passing in a single parameter.

Change-Id: Id947fe793c0df35c6a3b2fe2d984f310938ab3f5

commit_message:
Wait for nova to initialise

As the service dbsync's now happen in postconfigure.d nova is now
available some time after keystone. This commit adds a wait for the nova
api service in order to ensure we don't prematurely try to use nova.

This will be required once https://review.openstack.org/#/c/57466/ is
merged.

Change-Id: I6db65178b12df02b59c267b6d502c6bed1c6ac85

commit_message:
Fixes inconsistent usage of 'mount_point' in guestagent.

In trove.guestagent.datastore.mysql.manager.Manager#prepare
'mount_point' is taken from two different sources,
method parameter and CONF. It could cause issues when
parameter value differs from the one ftom CONF.
This patch fixes the issue.

It is suggested also to remove 'mount_point' parameter --
by a separate patch.

Fixes bug: 1248212

Change-Id: If8a93c475752d8cc3043883c73c1ae5ce4488701

commit_message:
Use auth_url as mgmt_url if not admin identity

If admin identity endpoint is not found from the returned service catalog,
the given message error is Unable to authorize user by shell.py, when
httpclient.py raises an AuthorizationFailure exception with the message
Current authorization does not have a known management url but this one
is suppressed by the message previously mentioned in shell.py, in order
to solve this bug it is possible to use the auth_url as management_url

Change-Id: I17cab45a0193a80d555b3d37408dd439f70676eb
Closes-Bug: #120899

In order to let grenade run tempest tests in parallel on virtual
environments we need to create the same tiny and micro guests that
we create in a normal devstack run. Otherwise we blow memory on

cake.

commit_message:
Don't specify a default instance size, create tiny and micro

In order to let grenade run tempest tests in parallel on virtual
environments we need to create the same tiny and micro guests that
we create in a normal devstack run. Otherwise we blow memory on
the environment, causing a scheduler fail, and sadness. Also no
cake.

Removing the explicit setting of DEFAULT_INSTANCE_TYPE will make
tempest create appropriate instance sizes, and use them in it's
guests.

Change-Id: I6adde22499853d0cde53771e83ebf5c5f7041c11
Partial-Bug: 1252170

commit_message:
Enable 'validators' attribute for each field.

Previously they were available only at form-level. Field-level
validators could be used to validate against different regexps (with
YAQL 'test' function, which is also added in this commit) and show
different messages.

Closes-bug: #1250823
Change-Id: I7d4e1119f1ad8651abe0c7ff3f6fb56ff7d84694

commit_message:
Isolate tests a bit more

This patch isolates mongodb tests and adds new `shortcut-methods` to
base clases in order to make it easier for subclasses to access conf
instances, override them or even hook them.

Change-Id: I8fe05bf383198244616499adb60480859f1ec7c6

commit_message:
Check if flavors exist before creating them.

* lib/tempest: When creating the m1.tiny and m1.nano flavors ensure that
they don't exist first. This is important for Grenade where code may be
run multiple times and should expect that some things preexist.

Change-Id: I1772d4334f39d612f8a187eb5311a1b2caee3953
