I revert my position."}, {'account_id': 7923, 'date': '2013-11-19 19:11:10.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

For the record, I'm quite convinced the version I suggest is OK :) To be fair I've not yet created a stack, but several tests seem to show that the syntax is correct (it should be anyway, since all other services use it).

And I'm also certain that the current version is not working:

gpocentek@os-ctrl:~$ keystone endpoint-create --service-id 59496dc98587400fb2a154f2be7488ae
--publicurl=http://os-ctrl:8804/v1/\$(tenant_id)s --adminurl=http://os-ctrl:8804/v1/\$(tenant_id)s --internalurl=http://os-ctrl:8804/v1/\$(tenant_id)s
-bash: syntax error near unexpected token `('

We could use double quotes to fix the problem, instead of the complete syntax change:

keystone endpoint-create --publicurl="http://controller:8004/v1/\$(tenant_id)s"'}, {'account_id': 4257, 'date': '2013-11-21 10:42:52.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Looks good to me, but someone else must approve

This patch essentially reverts Ic90bace1e60f3cfddf00dd5594cee5d083b75ae7, which IMO is the correct thing to do. As mentioned on the comment I just added, it wasn't broken before the patch - the user who reported a bug had added single quotes, but not removed the escapes. It was certainly broken after, though, because the escapes were removed without single quotes being added.

Double quotes is an option, though if we keep the $ then that will still need to be escaped. You'd need single quotes to avoid that, but that's probably a bad idea as it will break any environment variables appearing elsewhere in the string (e.g. for the hostname). So ideally I think we should add double quotes and switch back to % instead of $.

To recap, these forms will work (try them yourself in bash!):

  echo %\(true\)  # original
  echo "%(true)"  # preferred
  echo "\$(true)"
  echo \$\(true\)
  echo '%(true)'
  echo '$(true)'

These forms will *not* work (syntax error):

  echo %(true)
  echo \$(true)  # current

These forms will do the Wrong Thing:

  echo $(true)
  echo "$(true)"'}, {'account_id': 612, 'date': '2013-11-21 12:33:11.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Looks good to me (core reviewer)

commit_message:
Refactoring of networking-related tests

Remove manually built dicts containing networking parameters and use fixtures instead.
We always made same changes to these dicts when fixtures were changed
so they simply diplicated networking parameters which are present in fixtures.

Change-Id: I426d813c764aabff044a073ab7c98d95295bec4c

commit_message:
Do not automatically re-enable the compute service.

Compute service won't be automatically re-enabled, in case it was
manually disabled by an administrator.

Closes-Bug: #1251520
Change-Id: I58ca0bbef664f5605bc83b9555348e4292a738ed

commit_message:
Remove confusing message about mysql credentials

The Glance installation material contained a note indicating that if
connecting to MySQL fails the user should use the IP address of the
database server instead when specifying the credentials.

Besides being confusing in its wording this note referred to a situation
that the user could not possibly become aware of until starting the
Glance services later in the chapter.

Additionally no such warning is included elsewhere in the guide as its
presumed (via specification in the prerequisites up front) that the user
has set up their /etc/hosts files such that the controller host name will
resolve.

Change-Id: Ic5e6e1820628b0854effe7594b09610d030d0573
Closes-Bug: #1251458
backport:havana

commit_message:
enable Ironic password for keystone auth

The current version of the ironic-source.yaml uses AdminPassword, it
should use the ironic users password and not the admin user password.
The patch corrects an authentication error by adding IronicPassword
to ironic-source.yaml file.

Change-Id: Idbe4950bb3026e2201ddfddc4b58c2bf98972be9

commit_message:
Timeout if seed fails to get IP address

Prevent boot-seed-vm from getting stuck in a loop if the seed VM fails
to get an IP, this was causing CI to run indefinitely.

Change-Id: Ib3f44e538186af8e090e1065b4b708b6ce95442e

I also added options to allow for much more fine grained control of which elements to apply, and I'm not sure any of that functionality is applicable to disk-image-create either."}, {'account_id': 7144, 'date': '2013-11-18 12:32:28.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 8: (3 inline comments)

'}, {'account_id': 4190, 'date': '2013-11-18 21:26:54.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 10: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

@james

Yes - I think this patch is /much/ bigger than needed to what what you want, which is itself neither here nor there.

The problem though is that this means we now have two codepaths to run the same things, which have to be kept in sync. A few months ago we went through a tedious exercise to make ramdisk-image-create be a hardlink to diskimage-create to solve the very same problem you're introducing.

So - I'd really really really rather see this as a patch to the existing codebase - which I am sure will be small, isolated and not invasive."}, {'account_id': 7144, 'date': '2013-11-18 23:48:22.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 10:

I see your point about duplicated code paths.  But, I think this is relatively isolated to logic around handling of the elements path and calling dib-run-parts.

Overall, I don't think a patch to disk-image-create would be really all that much smaller given there's 5 or so arguments to add, plus new logic around the chroot handling, image building, etc.  Personally, I don't like the pattern of additional scripts hardlinked to disk-image-create and then logic around what to actually do based on the script filename.  In my opinion, that is not a pattern that scales well, especially when you start considering the need to disable/enable options and flags due to some not always being applicable depending on how you were called.  E.g., show_options could become quite unruly if there were a proliferation of IS_* things everywhere.

Additionally, the inability to easily run and write unit tests is critical when you start adding more divergent paths to bash scripts.

There may be some future value in having a more feature rich python module implementation around d-i-b style elements.  And, while what I've done isn't completely re-useable in that sense, there is a basic framework there (Element Class, Runner class, unit tests).  I certainly don't have any specifics around what these future desires might be, so I don't want to present this point as having more weight than it's due, but generally, it seems useful.

Those reasons are why I chose this route. It seemed more natural to me to attempt to expand the tooling around elements themselves in the existing diskimage_builder python module instead of adding to disk-image-create.

That being said, if we're at an impasse in terms of getting this merged and you view the cons winning out on this one, then feel free to -2, and I'll consider a different approach."}, {'account_id': 6488, 'date': '2013-11-20 05:28:33.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 10: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

Just weighing in, I agree with lifeless that just patching the existing tools will be less invasive than writing a ton of new slightly different code.

And the symlink approach is just one way to go about avoiding unintended divergent behavior. We can also just make a policy of nothing but options handling and library calls in entry points. That is really a separate issue from everything else discussed in the review.

I have been where you are a few times James; there's some great code here and we know it works. However, there is a nuance that we've been through before, and have decided to handle by pushing the code paths into the same place whenever possible."}, {'account_id': 7144, 'date': '2013-11-21 12:40:35.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 10: Abandoned

Fair enough, I understand the intent for wanting this in disk-image-create instead of diskimage_builder.

I suspect my motivation for not doing that is likely why the element dependency logic is not there as well, but just guessing really.

I still maintain this is not a ton of new, slightly different code.  It's different, and different enough I chose to do it within the existing diskimage_builder module instead of disk-image-create.

Certainly I agree it would be a *much* smaller patchset if done all in bash.  Disabling or undoing 4 or 5 steps, plus there would be no unit tests, so there's almost a 50% reduction, as well as much less inline documentation with no docstrings.

I'll put this one to rest, since it's certainly not my intent to add the functionality at the expense of additional complexity if the complexity is deemed not warranted."}]

commit_message:
Add ability to apply elements to current system.

This commit adds the ability to apply diskimage-builder style elements
to the current system, as opposed to a chroot.  The functionality is
implemented in new python modules under diskimage_builder.  A script
using this python code at bin/element-runner is also included.  There
are some simple test elements under diskimage_builder/tests/elements to
aid with testing/verification as well.

Change-Id: Ic2bcb8b9f17e03709048ee4702270ede9a95d064

Fix tox.ini to run tests in lockutils wrapper.

Without this line locks while parallel tests running won't be
working and there will be tests fails because of this.

Change-Id: I5d29441365fafd8005ac9a2088badca23bf7cb09

commit_message:
Refresh request.user on session updates

Update the request.user Whenever the user related information
is updated in the session, to make sure they are always sync.

Change-Id: Ie803db0784971d1dc350527d9f43a1120759774f
Closes-bug: 1247186

commit_message:
Highlight use of 'file' Glance backend

Highlight the use of the 'file' Glance backend for storage and the
default location that images will be stored under this scheme. Also
provide some guidance on the amount of space this will require.

Change-Id: I412c938d5f2151b3f3f76d47542d25d67c1c9869
Closes-bug: #1239516
backport: havana
(cherry picked from commit eec6cdb7be32799e3a56fd5d7000d4c0435e7158)

commit_message:
Add swift roles to keystone

Tenants using swift will require these roles :
  swiftoperator - manage tenants, container and ACL's
  ResellerAdmin - create and delete accounts

Both are required by tempest tests.

Change-Id: I71f58964df74804f351a96ef079e53cdd17980a5

commit_message:
Handle COPY verb in account quota middleware

Since COPY verb allow to copy an existing object
we must check the size of the source object before
allowing the copy.

Fixes bug: #1201884

Change-Id: Ia37bc716be0c3e5a3174dc4370bb5084f81073ad

commit_message:
Proper update of objects

This patch fixes of updating rally.objects.{Task|Deployment} objects.
Now, objects have got a correct update of an encapsulated value of
internal representation of objects.

Change-Id: Iad775974c75bf28a83631753894eceafef06f6ab
Implements: blueprint independent-deploy

'}, {'account_id': 7191, 'date': '2013-10-26 04:50:25.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

I'm not sure about this. Why? This happens for a reason when you use a token/endpoint auth method you should use that token and not anything that gets fetched.

I'm not saying that it's right, but let me know what problem this is causing because we might need to do something more substantial."}, {'account_id': 4328, 'date': '2013-10-28 11:11:43.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

@Jamie Lennox: As I mentioned in the bug, the issue is that trust-scoping doesn't work.  You pass an unscoped token in to the constructor, then request a new (scoped) token via the authenticate(), but the client still sends the initial, unscoped token.

I'm not sure I understand any situation where you don't want to use the most recently acquired token, ie that in auth_ref.

Also consder the situation where you pass a token into a client object with a long lifetime, then with the current code, self.auth_ref.will_expire_soon is never called, so the client will end up sending an expired token instead of reauthenticating.

Arguably auth_token_from_user should not even exist, and there should be one location where the stored token is persisted, in auth_ref."}, {'account_id': 4, 'date': '2013-11-15 15:32:25.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Agree that 'auth_token_from_user' probably shouldn't exist, or should be a boolean, maybe? The intention of that attribute is to communicate that the user authenticated with token/endpoint rather than deriving a token from credentials, and therefore the token can't be refreshed or otherwise managed by the client."}, {'account_id': 4328, 'date': '2013-11-15 17:45:26.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

@Dolph Mathews: Thanks for the feedback, but I'm still not sure ignoring explicit calls to authenticate() makes sense - surely the token passed in to the constructor is just another type of credential, not some immutable thing which can never be refreshed or re-scoped?

The issue here is that to obtain a v2 trust scoped token, you have to do it via the authenticate(), not the constructor, ref https://review.openstack.org/#/c/48462/ - if you're saying that the token passed into the constructor is immutable, then this can never work, unless you use username/password auth.

The necessity to re-scope in the authenticate() is a restriction of the underlying API, but preventing getting a trust-scoped token when a user authenticates with a token instead of username/password is purely a keystoneclient limitation, AFAICT, based on the concept of token immutability which you describe, which does not reflect the behavior of the underlying API, hence IMHO it's bogus.

If this really is as designed then all calls to authenticate() when the client object was created with a token should fail, rather than succeeding and silently ignoring the result (this is not what I want btw ;)"}, {'account_id': 7244, 'date': '2013-11-15 19:37:00.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Looks good to me, but someone else must approve

'}, {'account_id': 2218, 'date': '2013-11-20 15:58:32.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Refreshing of Tokens and enforcement of that workflow is done on the server side.  The client should be able to request a token for a token, Trust or no, as that new token cannot get a longer lifespan than the original.  With the upcoming changes in "revoke" by expires_at, we will also makes sure they are all revoked together.'}, {'account_id': 2218, 'date': '2013-11-20 15:58:38.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Looks good to me (core reviewer)

'}, {'account_id': 4, 'date': '2013-11-20 20:16:18.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Looks good to me (core reviewer); Approved

commit_message:
Avoid returning stale token via auth_token property

The auth_ref token should take precedence over the user provided
token, since any call to authenticate() will update the auth_ref,
rendering the auth_token_from_user stale.

Change-Id: Ibc86dca840f4b8dd23856735616ee48a7b397fcd
Closes-Bug: #1244675

Add performance metrics field to image locations DB model

Glance maintain a performance metrics dictionary for each image location
entry, it can be used to store different indicators.

blueprint: weight-based-storage-selection

commit_message:
Add pyudev to neutron requirement

ML2 plugin is required for neutron in icehouse, neutron-server needs
pyudev for binding, device and software management to enable ML2 plugin.

Fixes bug 1250311

Change-Id: I79af9d285adb0b9f7d8b891e40fa053b8c2892ab

commit_message:
Add verbose output to all stat commands

When you stat a container or object with the verbose flag the full path of the
reousrce will be displayed with the token similarlly to how an account stat
displays the auth url and token.

 * move some logic out of bin/swift.st_stat to test it
 * new module swiftclient.commnad_helpers for code you want to test
 * moved prt_bytes into swiftclient.utils to test it
 * fixed IndexError with prt_bytes on sizes >= 1024Y

Change-Id: Iaaa96e0308b08c554205b0055b8a04de581fefa4

revisions:
[{'created': '2013-11-18 15:20:55.000000000', 'message': 'Use env variables as tripleo-cd cloud params

Currently, tripleo-cd element runs devtest-overcloud.sh script
passing all parameters used as positional arguments. Given the
fact that we already have 9 of them, it would be much more
readable and less error-prone to pass them using env variables
instead (additionally, this would allow us to use those params
in hand execute version of devtest guide).

This change must be approved only together with the corresponding
one to tripleo-incubator devtest-overcloud.sh script.

commit_message:
Use env variables as tripleo-cd cloud params

Currently, tripleo-cd element runs devtest-overcloud.sh script
passing all parameters used as positional arguments. Given the
fact that we already have 9 of them, it would be much more
readable and less error-prone to pass them using env variables
instead (additionally, this would allow us to use those params
in hand execute version of devtest guide).

This change must be approved only together with the corresponding
one to tripleo-incubator devtest-overcloud.sh script.

Change-Id: I68e4e659852c8549ad96fd7bf3f10957b652e648

commit_message:
Don't delete environment in case there are problems with RabbitMQ.

Environment should be deleted from muranoapi db only when conductor is
available via RabbitMQ.

Closes-bug: #1236293

Currently, devtest_overcloud doc contains stack-create overcloud
call, which accepts parameters, that we don't expose to users in
devtest story (e.g. NeutronPublicInterfaceDefaultRoute). It would
be less confusing to users, if we passed only parameters, that
are defined in devtest doc and rely on defaults of the overcloud
template for the rest of parameters.

Change-Id: Iec097bee09ff06997fcfd7a4ec4a3d639ad6c77f
"}]
commit_message:
Use separate stack-create overcloud call in docs

Currently, devtest_overcloud doc contains stack-create overcloud
call, which accepts parameters, that we don't expose to users in
devtest story (e.g. NeutronPublicInterfaceDefaultRoute). It would
be less confusing to users, if we passed only parameters, that
are defined in devtest doc and rely on defaults of the overcloud
template for the rest of parameters.

Change-Id: Iec097bee09ff06997fcfd7a4ec4a3d639ad6c77f

[{'created': '2013-11-18 15:21:04.000000000', 'message': "Fix floating ips when devtest.sh is hand executed

When devtest.sh is hand executed, the public interface of the
network node in overcloud is not added to br-ex bridge, which
makes floating ips unusable. This is caused by the fact that
we don't set the name of the public interface in devtest guide
(it's in devtest.sh, but it's not put to generated html doc).

Closes-Bug: #1252304

Change-Id: I9035b5ab26498954b46051f1b9bb982f0bc07c86

commit_message:
Fix floating ips when devtest.sh is hand executed

When devtest.sh is hand executed, the public interface of the
network node in overcloud is not added to br-ex bridge, which
makes floating ips unusable. This is caused by the fact that
we don't set the name of the public interface in devtest guide
(it's in devtest.sh, but it's not put to generated html doc).

Closes-Bug: #1252304

Change-Id: I9035b5ab26498954b46051f1b9bb982f0bc07c86

commit_message:
Highlight use of 'file' Glance backend

Highlight the use of the 'file' Glance backend for storage and the
default location that images will be stored under this scheme. Also
provide some guidance on the amount of space this will require.

Change-Id: I412c938d5f2151b3f3f76d47542d25d67c1c9869
Closes-bug: #1239516

commit_message:
Use env variables as tripleo-cd cloud params

Currently, tripleo-cd element runs devtest-overcloud.sh script
passing all parameters used as positional arguments. Given the
fact that we already have 9 of them, it would be much more
readable and less error-prone to pass them using env variables
instead (additionally, this would allow us to use those params
in hand execute version of devtest guide).

Backwards compatibility is retained by accepting parameters both
as positional arguments and environment variables. Positional
arguments take precedence over environment variables.

Change-Id: Ieb3e9373c6f4364b8c83ac4ebe19268957c770c1

commit_message:
API accepts UUID for ports only

The MAC address may be changed, so it is not suitable to accept MAC
as filter for GET/PATCH/DELETE actions.

Change-Id: I249a984545ff50efb73e1ce8702be5407c15ebb7
Closes-Bug: 1246816

commit_message:
Fix the wrong db configuration variable in sample cinder.conf

Base on the cinder.openstack.common.db.sqlalchemy.session, the db
related values should be in [database] group

2. you should merge the two test cases into a single one and rename it accordingly (maybe look at the snapshot tests as a naming sample)"}, {'account_id': 6737, 'date': '2013-09-09 23:19:56.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

Giulio,

Devstack does not enable backup by default (at least mine does not).

While I would like to see these tests run on every run of tempest, I still think is a good idea to have the option to disable backup tests since not everyone will want to have to setup and swift or ceph cluster in order to run the tests.

I will merge the tests as requested.'}, {'account_id': 6796, 'date': '2013-09-09 23:38:32.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

hi Edward,

I think devstack is doing it, look here:
https://github.com/openstack-dev/devstack/blob/master/lib/cinder#L507

regarding the boolean option, I'm also fine with keeping it then, but I'd set it to True by default then"}, {'account_id': 6737, 'date': '2013-09-09 23:48:16.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

Hi Giulio,

If you look here you will see that c-bak is not enabled by default:

https://github.com/openstack-dev/devstack/blob/master/stackrc#L35

Adds cinder-backup functional tests

commit_message:
Make the modules eventlet friendly as early as possible

eventlet monkey patch must happens before any reference can made to a
not patched version of the classes.

For example if an import module gets a logger before monkey patching,
it can made reference to not patched version of the modules.

The late patching can lead to bad performance, strange behavior or even to dead lock.

Now the monkey patch happens on module load, so it cannot be unit
tested as it was tested before.
The eventlet monkey patching happens even before the module's main function called.

Change-Id: I7db37b6a6b15e0038c028bafd6c9f1f09f258955

commit_message:
Removal of extra vim configuration comment

The #vim tabstop=4 shiftwidth=4 softtabstop=4 has been removed
from the beginning lines of source files in oslo except for
/tests folder

Fixes bug : 1229324

Change-Id: Ibbf43ac902fa94894ef6186ad8835c6dd1c3282e

commit_message:
Adds nova vif plugin for contrail/vrouter

OpenContrail System consists of two main components:
OpenContrail Controller and the OpenContrail vRouter.

- OpenContrail Controller is a logically centralized but physically distributed SDN controller
- OpenContrail vRouter is a forwarding plane (of a distributed router)
  that runs in the hypervisor of a virtualized server.
- This patch implements the nova vif driver for the vRouter.
- Corresponding neutron changes are at changeid
     I547426f1d4e0d1a305e179a785a5d517d058c381

Change-Id: Idef828f31b4d54f44f595c70aaea825cc2adf2cc
Implements: blueprint juniper-opencontrail-vrouter-nova-vif-driver
Closes-Bug: #1246837

[{'created': '2013-10-31 18:55:01.000000000', 'message': 'Initial verison of capabilities interface

This is intial verison of capabitilities interface, that allow add
special attributes to drivers method that will indicate that this method
support special feature.

For example some of method can be marked as stateless and volume

commit_message:
Capabilities for any Cinder method to indicate special behavior.

For example some volume driver method can be marked as @stateless and
taskflow code will not change volume status upon calling this method.

Change-Id: If2f6ebc240c8b0fc5fa2bc37c5038a58b6cda831

[{'created': '2013-10-07 01:33:02.000000000', 'message': 'Fix unbound reference with multiple nics attached

An unbound reference results in an undeleteable stack and in
some cases a general wedging of nova.  In the delete path,
an assumption was made that a port and net would have matching
network identifiers.  In the delete path this is not always
the case, such as when multiple nics are attached to a system.

Change-Id: I8c676f82bfa85c8b550b3ed14e55e60a41062e97
Closes-Bug: 1236116
Closes-Bug: 1235897
'}]
commit_message:
Fix unbound reference with multiple nics attached

An unbound reference results in an undeleteable stack and in
some cases a general wedging of nova.  In the delete path,
an assumption was made that a port and net would have matching
network identifiers.  In the delete path this is not always
the case, such as when multiple nics are attached to a system.

Change-Id: I8c676f82bfa85c8b550b3ed14e55e60a41062e97
Closes-Bug: 1236116
Closes-Bug: 1235897

commit_message:
Replace uuidutils.generate_uuid() with str(uuid.uuid4())

uuidutils.generate_uuid() is going to be removed from oslo,
so we need to remove its use in ceilometer.

This patch was use str(uuid.uuid4()) to replace
uuidutils.generate_uuid().

Change-Id: I311b65af33e36680cd801b07753a9b5f1a3e2b48
Closes-Bug: #1253497

'}, {'account_id': 2860, 'date': '2013-10-25 14:37:06.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 11: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

Mehdi, the new patch basically creates 4 sessions, that is
4 transactions, and they are all nested which should be
really avoided. I think there should be a query and add if
not exists, so that there are not many sessions created. This
way, for exists users, projects, the cost is a query, vs. 4
transactions each time and the exceptions. I think serialize
the queries and add, so it will be something like this.

query, add user (possible add transaction 1)
query, add project (possible add transaction 2)
query, add resource (possible add transaction 3)
then update.

doing this, I believe in most cases, you still maintain 
1 transactions. since the query will have a hit. vs, now,
you have transactions nested."}, {'account_id': 2813, 'date': '2013-10-25 14:42:20.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 11: Work In Progress'}, {'account_id': 2813, 'date': '2013-10-25 14:48:40.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 11:

litong01: They already have a 'add only if not exists' statement to not create the additional session.

But I agree that the code looks crappy. And after some tests it fix my issue with postgresql but don't work with mysql. commit_message:
make record_metering_data concurrency safe

Recording metering might happen in parallel, and if two sqlalchemy
session try to create a source, a user, a project or a resource at the
same time, one of them fail with a IntegrityError.

This patch ensure the record_metering_data sqlalchemy session always
have the needed source, user, project and a resource by creating missing
obj in an other sqlalchemy session.

Fixes bug: #1237671

Change-Id: Ie8761ce1615c3142ad6ad2a400537f465f3bbf0a

commit_message:
Replace uuidutils.generate_uuid() with uuid.uuid4() in cinder

uuidutils.generate_uuid() is going to be removed from oslo, so we
need to remove its use in cinder.

This patch was use uuid.uuid4() to replace uuidutils.generate_uuid().

Change-Id: I8aaea61c1d5b15a22187ab9e4a6d6791f5244c37
Closes-Bug: #1253497

commit_message:
Remove import uuid for some files

In some files, it import both uuid and uuidutils, but actually
uuidutils already include the main logic of uuid, so we can remove
"import uuid" from those files and use left "import uuidutils".

Implements part of bp no-import-uuid

Change-Id: Id71f1d4cc0de49c6b3c48135008ae1b704a9ca9b

revisions:
[{'created': '2013-11-21 02:39:38.000000000', 'message': "Ensure that the default instance sizes are nano and micro

In order to let grenade run tempest tests in parallel on virtual
environments we need to create the same nano and micro guests that
we create in a normal devstack run. Otherwise we blow memory on
the environment, causing a scheduler fail, and sadness. Also no
cake.

We can't just remove the explicit setting of DEFAULT_INSTANCE_TYPE
as it then tries to recreate nano and micro flavors and fails. So
we hard code the the nano and micro flavor ids for the config file.

This is probably the wrong way to go about it, but just trying it
to see if this fixes the gate problem

Change-Id: I278fcc3f1ec3a2ea0ed27c7f0cddb683a5875115
Partial-bug: 1252170
"}]
commit_message:
Ensure that the default instance sizes are nano and micro

In order to let grenade run tempest tests in parallel on virtual
environments we need to create the same nano and micro guests that
we create in a normal devstack run. Otherwise we blow memory on
the environment, causing a scheduler fail, and sadness. Also no
cake.

We can't just remove the explicit setting of DEFAULT_INSTANCE_TYPE
as it then tries to recreate nano and micro flavors and fails. So
we hard code the the nano and micro flavor ids for the config file.

This is probably the wrong way to go about it, but just trying it
to see if this fixes the gate problem

Change-Id: I278fcc3f1ec3a2ea0ed27c7f0cddb683a5875115
Partial-bug: 1252170

commit_message:
Set swift timeouts higher

Devstack is commonly run in a small slow environment, so bump the
timeouts up.

node_timeout is how long between read operations a node takes to
respond to the proxy server
conn_timeout is all about how long it takes a connect() system call to
return

Change-Id: Ib437466a3fc9274b8aa49b19e4fe7fa26f553419
Co-Authored-By: Peter Portante <peter.portante@redhat.com>
Related-Bug: #1252514

commit_message:
Fix i18N compliance with non-existant keypair

when test stack-create in Japanese language environment,
execute "heat stack-create" with non-existant keypair
"heat_key", UnicodeDecodeError will occur because
exception message has not been decoded correctly for
the following process:
(_("%(message)s") % ('message': ...)).

This patch uses safe_decode function in strutils module
to resolve the error.

Change-Id: I57cddae1b73a95cb9298daf51e49d5d7729467d9
Closes-Bug: #1249224

commit_message:
Enable polling minimization

In some cases the OVS agent might end up wiring a port for a VM
several seconds after the VM has booted. As a result, there is a
risk that the VM won't receive an IP address from DHCP in time.

This patch changes the default value for agent.minimize_polling to
True. This change should reduce the time needed for configuring
an interface on br-int consistently.

Change-Id: I009f606fd34a132376f1d50f8ccda9d35d064bfa
Related-bug: 1224001

commit_message:
Add configurable ovsdb monitor respawn interval

If minimize_polling=True and the ovsdb-client process died, the
default respawn interval of 0 would mean that we'd start polling
again. This patch adds the option ovsdb_monitor_respawn_interval and
defaults it to 30 seconds.

Change-Id: I12c1e05ec4d6d2bd4d84024a91116e2ac3974868
Close-Bug: 1243867

Looking at the comments on https://review.openstack.org/56447 I realized there's a bit of a problem with this code.

Alex Gaynor stated the obvious which I had completely missed:
> I don't understand how thsi is possible, the definition of `connection.execute` is: `c = self.cursor(); c.execute(*arsg); return c`

Of course, since the DB connection overrides conn.cursor(), that means the execute is under two different timers, one from GreenDBConnection and one from GreenDBCursor. So the connection version becomes redundant.

Making a new patch set which eliminates this redundant code."}, {'account_id': 9129, 'date': '2013-11-19 17:32:52.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 3.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-11-19 19:27:28.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3: Doesn't seem to work

commit_message:
Fixed concurrent PUT requests to accounts or containers

When concurrent PUT requests come in for an account or container, the
resulting DB access will try to lock the DB for writing. Normal access
will retry when it encounters a locked DB, change 0fdad0d9 introduced
a cursor for doing the initialization which did not have the retry
capability, resulting in a hard failure.

Fixes bug 1243973

commit_message:
Move Loadbalancer Noop driver to the unit tests

Move Loadbalancer Noop driver to the corresponding folder in
unit tests to clearly indicate that it is an utility driver
that only suitable for unit testing.

Closes-Bug: #1250767
Change-Id: Ide2ebf212193f2cf5da9cf7a7f068fd918a55ada

commit_message:
add test for create_backup

*add positive test and corresponding client for server
action: createBackup.
*verify that create backup successfully and rotate
backups correctly.
*add the property prefix filter support in image_list_detail
of the image service client, because the image api in nova can't
support sort_dir='asc' and sort_key='created_at'.
so we can submit request like the following to get specified images

GET /images/detail?sort_key=created_at&property-image_type=backup

Change-Id: I43337970e4b1b71c7290416c517a8f93152b168f

commit_message:
SQLite behavior independent DB test cases

Currently, cleanups in DB test cases rely on the fact, that SQLite
in-memory DB is always used. To be able to run those test cases on RDBMS
like MySQL and PostgreSQL we must make sure that all created tables are
dropped and that test cases use a newly created SQLAlchemy engine
instance. Currently used a kind of Singleton. An instance of sqlalchemy
engine declared globally and reusing until it will be cleaned. Thus
session.cleanup() call is required to destroy engine where it was
created.

Blueprint: tests-given-db-backend
Change-Id: I81d1ac2804dc7434f7ed1f36206f39f777480398

commit_message:
os._exit in _start_child may cause unexpected exception

In _start_child, we may os._exit(status).
status is set by the return value of _child_wait_for_exit_or_signal.
, where status may be None.
And defensive coding to prevent the unexpected exceptions

Change-Id: I4b89147225cc9e848a97816f171f77236bd23b2c

commit_message:
Ensure get_pid_to_kill works with rootwrap script

To ensure that correct process is killed when using a rootwrap
script, we must recursively list the children of our top-level
process and kill the last one. This patch uses the psutil python
module which is already used in the heat-cfntools project.

Change-Id: I702bb9dd794c08fcaab637284ee303de1778cbb9

I think it's genius! :-)
I am not suggesting heaps of these, but as a basic "does the server startup and serve something" - it's a good catch IMO. So to give the tempest jobs some more confidence in passing.
Struggling to see the problem... but what ever.'}, {'account_id': 1561, 'date': '2013-11-19 21:54:23.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

but does it add any additional real coverage if the devstack gate job is doing the exact same thing?'}, {'account_id': 1561, 'date': '2013-11-19 22:09:00.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

Here's a thought ... I don't think tempest is pluggable to the degree that devstack is, for example.  We're not going to get functional tests into tempest in the short term.  Maybe we should start a functional test suite in the tree for now?  This could be a start to that."}, {'account_id': 1561, 'date': '2013-11-19 22:23:20.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Just spoke to sdague (QA PTL) about this:

<russellb> sdague: for a stackforge project, does just building a functional test suite within their own tree to start with make sense?  and that could eventually be ported into tempest?

<sdague> russellb: yes, I think for stackforge pre-incubation, having your own functional test suite makes the most sense
<sdague> that runs in a devstack contenxt

commit_message:
Reverse the quota reservation in revert_resize

If concurrent revert_resize requests happen, the second request
will fail because of save failure. In such situation, we should
revert the reservation.

Change-Id: I90f4189ec385ea323e62312e519ae65ec58cca66
Signed-off-by: Yunhong Jiang <yunhong.jiang@intel.com>

commit_message:
Have tox install via setup.py develop

tox 1.6 was released, which means that we can now take advantage of the
feature we added to it - which is using setup.py develop to install the
code into the virtualenv. The logic was taken from run_tests.sh - so the
performance issues around using tox vs. using install_venv should now be
gone.

Ported from Nova: 32d63a9fbe6f353ca1af8922d6bcbb012a2cc32c
Change-Id: If83a5b5473344d3a0e3a3a9fbb4ba16fa75f5be3

commit_message:
nsd4slave backend

This backend sends nsd-control commands to a remote NSD4 server. It
depends on the multi backend and on another master backend, most likely
PowerDNS.

Change-Id: I722210de97b207d318f300092f4e3be08e894961
Implements: blueprint nsd4-slave-backend

commit_message:
Bootstrap Messages support

This patch implements some of the operations required to add Message
support to marconiclient. The higher level implementation of message
deletion is not present in this patch, since it requires the definition
of a new Message type, which will submitted in the upcoming patch.

Partially-Implements blueprint python-marconiclient-v1
Partially-Implements blueprint messages-management

Change-Id: I42efe24e0e6083c530d494e95b66c6c01535a849

-------

Unit tests are progressing. More of them are green, and the cause of
the remaining breaks is starting to become clear. In the case, where a
queue or project that does not exist is queried, say, accidentally,

failing for this reason.

'}, {'created': '2013-10-31 17:10:12.000000000', 'message': "feat: connect sharding manager to control drivers

This patch implements the register/deregister/lookup operations for
the sharding manager.

As a result of this patch, the sharding driver now takes the control
driver as a paramater. This gives it the access needed to make
decisions about queue placement (and lookups) based on the entries in
the control plane.

In order to get the sharding manager working correctly, several
methods had to be overridden to properly handle the QueueNotMapped
error. When a QueueNotMapped error is encountered under normal
conditions, it is equivalent to the target resource not being
found. The overrides mimic the default behavior of those controllers'
methods in the case where the queue isn't found.

Up next: caching, sharded queue listing support.

commit_message:
feat: connect sharding manager to control drivers

This patch implements the register/deregister/lookup operations for
the sharding manager.

As a result of this patch, the sharding driver now takes the control
driver as a paramater. This gives it the access needed to make
decisions about queue placement (and lookups) based on the entries in
the control plane.

In order to get the sharding manager working correctly, several
methods had to be overridden to properly handle the QueueNotMapped
error. When a QueueNotMapped error is encountered under normal
conditions, it is equivalent to the target resource not being
found. The overrides mimic the default behavior of those controllers'
methods in the case where the queue isn't found.

An inconsistency was found between the base storage driver and the
concrete implementations. message_controller.list did not provide an
include_claimed parameter. This has been corrected.

To avoid DuplicateOptErrors in the mongodb driver in a sharded
context, a filtering algorithm is applied. To make it clear to data
drivers that they need to apply this filtering algorithm, conf.dynamic
is set by the sharding driver.

Unit tests have been added for the weighted select algorithm.

Up next: sharded queue listing support, caching

Change-Id: Ic36cd657ba13fa4c0b624dc5c71bfe99f9a70139
Partitally-implements: blueprint storage-sharding

[{'created': '2013-11-20 16:50:29.000000000', 'message': "DO NOT MERGE: disable libvirt lifecycle events

There has been a lot of gate instability this week, and the biggest
offender is bug 1251920.  It's not clear what is causing the problem
just yet.  This patch is just to test one possibility.

The use of libvirt lifecycle events was merged a while ago (grizzly
timeframe), but was not actually being used until much more recently due
to bug 1220278.

This patch disables libvirt lifecycle events just to see if it makes
tests pass reliably.

Change-Id: Ia47ac8cd74be708d8ba70c316ba43e028c764315

commit_message:
DO NOT MERGE: disable libvirt lifecycle events

There has been a lot of gate instability this week, and the biggest
offender is bug 1251920.  It's not clear what is causing the problem
just yet.  This patch is just to test one possibility.

The use of libvirt lifecycle events was merged a while ago (grizzly
timeframe), but was not actually being used until much more recently due
to bug 1220278.

This patch disables libvirt lifecycle events just to see if it makes
tests pass reliably.

Change-Id: Ia47ac8cd74be708d8ba70c316ba43e028c764315

commit_message:
Added a check for HTTP_X_IDENTITY_STATUS

If keystone is configured to run in 'delay_auth_decision' mode it will
pass the token, along with the HTTP header X-Identity-Status set to
'Invalid'. This check for this, and returns a 401

Closes-Bug: #1253074

Change-Id: Ia531f73f98418594f867f3c2849865c26b13e18d

commit_message:
Make Deploy and Task objects similar

The objects have got a similar interface methods: __init__, get, delete,
delete_by_uuid. The API of DB was also changed.

Change-Id: I7c5962c14b2dd701b9c474d8c5cd8b5198621dd5
Implements: blueprint independent-deploy

commit_message:
Detect udevd version and behave accordingly.

We can no longer rely on the name of the udevd binary as a hint for its
version, so instead we query the binary and behave accordingly.

Change-Id: Id4c869dfeeca5ed970169343b6b5f0f2c4499ca3

revisions:
[{'created': '2013-11-20 08:38:32.000000000', 'message': 'Fix filter name for puppetdb

When creating the filter class name the last part is not capitalized.
So Swift::Storage::Filter::Healthcheck[bla] is named
Swift::Storage::Filter::healthcheck[bla].  Puppet don't detect the
syntax error as the resource is "created" within a string.  But
puppetdb's parser do not let this work.

This fix it and adjust the tests.

Change-Id: If11c3ad0e98d14b9387b3daa4afeb118387100f8
Closes-Bug: #1252998
'}]
commit_message:
Fix filter name for puppetdb

When creating the filter class name the last part is not capitalized.
So Swift::Storage::Filter::Healthcheck[bla] is named
Swift::Storage::Filter::healthcheck[bla].  Puppet don't detect the
syntax error as the resource is "created" within a string.  But
puppetdb's parser do not let this work.

This fix it and adjust the tests.

Change-Id: If11c3ad0e98d14b9387b3daa4afeb118387100f8
Closes-Bug: #1252998

[{'created': '2013-11-15 03:19:23.000000000', 'message': "Tune up report and downtime intervals for l2 agent

If the neutron server erroneously thinks than the l2 agent is down
it will fail to bind a port, which can lead to VM's spawn errors.
However, the issue is only transient because the agent effectively
is only 'late' in reporting back.

Best solution would be an alpha-count algorithm (so that we can detect
persistent failures more reliably), but for now let's be more tolerant
assuming that the agent is down by waiting at least twice the report
interval plus a tiny teeny bit.

Close-bug: #1244255

Cherry picked from (I544135ce1f6b7eaefb34ac44af8f5844d92ddd95)

Conflicts:

	neutron/agent/common/config.py

Change-Id: I21ab70d8262aa2ab857d67a49d65a947a1521022
"}]
commit_message:
Tune up report and downtime intervals for l2 agent

If the neutron server erroneously thinks than the l2 agent is down
it will fail to bind a port, which can lead to VM's spawn errors.
However, the issue is only transient because the agent effectively
is only 'late' in reporting back.

Best solution would be an alpha-count algorithm (so that we can detect
persistent failures more reliably), but for now let's be more tolerant
assuming that the agent is down by waiting at least twice the report
interval plus a tiny teeny bit.

Close-bug: #1244255

Cherry picked from (I544135ce1f6b7eaefb34ac44af8f5844d92ddd95)

Conflicts:

	neutron/agent/common/config.py

Change-Id: I21ab70d8262aa2ab857d67a49d65a947a1521022

commit_message:
[PRD-2520] Public network is untagged by default

Nova-Network default network assignment was changed.
Now it is the same as in case of Neutron provider.

Some little refactoring is made in NetworkManager/NeutronManager.

Change-Id: I41b1c0c32421669dd75629a3d63d171a88d50bc4

Amending the TC charter language to reflect gender parity.

In keeping with the spirit of the charter, enforcing the
OpenStack ideals of Openness, Transparency, Commonality,
Integration, Quality, this patch supports language that
reflects gender parity.

commit_message:
Support building wheels (PEP-427)

With that, building and uploading wheels to PyPI is only one "python
setup.py bdist_wheel" away.

Also, changes LC_ALL from C to UTF-8 to get around a bug in pip:

https://github.com/pypa/pip/issues/761

Remove the systemctl daemon-reload commands

These aren't needed during an image build and keep getting
copied each time a new service unit is added.

Change-Id: I498a229b69e78a3eca06bf8691c13157ecd6739d

commit_message:
Fix GroupAffinityFilter and GroupAntiAffinityFilter doc

The hint key is 'group' and not 'group_hosts', and the hint value is an
arbitrary value and not an instance UUID.

Change-Id: If2a034f727e09172dc5bf3d42a9c205df449ca72
Closes-Bug: #1223242
backport: havana
(cherry picked from commit 5b9d40cf28c69662cb9d27cd55a513f00adfcdaa)

commit_message:
Correct name of Ceilometer central agent service for Fedora and EL

Fedora and EL-based operating systems use the name
"openstack-ceilometer-central" for this service rather than
"openstack-ceilometer-agent-central.

As such while there is overlap with the instructions for openSUSE and
SLES this slight difference needs to be accounted for.

Change-Id: I8f922cafd35e1eedfa8d00f14cf07acbeefe842f
backport: havana
Closes-Bug: #1252265
(cherry picked from commit aaf0480fe3a0f6473ecfc238e04c3e57fe900d09)

installation, required to complete the procedure.

(cherry picked from commit 1215a0cba1f7b09963caea4a9a566629d5aff658)

[{'created': '2013-11-20 11:03:41.000000000', 'message': "Fix neutron credentials in nova config file

Currently, neutron_admin_username option is not set, so it
defaults to 'null'. This breaks nova-api and nova-compute
when they are talking to neutron-server.

Closes-Bug: #1253043

Change-Id: Iec07a6e6e99f65fdb759c6820f66342f10080ac2
"}]
commit_message:
Fix neutron credentials in nova config file

Currently, neutron_admin_username option is not set, so it
defaults to 'null'. This breaks nova-api and nova-compute
when they are talking to neutron-server.

Closes-Bug: #1253043

Change-Id: Iec07a6e6e99f65fdb759c6820f66342f10080ac2

commit_message:
Replace qpid_host with qpid_hostname

This patch replaces `qpid_host` with `qpid_hostname` in both the
qpid manifest and the spec file class. `qpid_host` has been shipped
as the parameter to specify qpid's hostname, although the correct one is
`qpid_hostname`.

Closes-bug 1242715

(cherry picked from commit 8eee78c69d6e29aa1151bf80e69d420bf9fbb838)

Conflicts:
	manifests/notify/qpid.pp

Change-Id: I6fe9f97b60cb155eca8a35ea65f8eac6a6c08f4d

commit_message:
Implemented bugfix for bug 1252989

I find bug after rebase my api unit tests to the latest master. We forgot
to add 'cfg.CONF.import('opt_name', 'climate.config')

Change-Id: I6c996c738bf3b2ae0b2c6d14beed424f99db4859

commit_message:
[1247283] Use IP ranges for Public in Neutron

In v.3.2 IP address space for Public network is defined using CIDR.
Now it is defined through IP ranges and network mask.
Some network configuration checks are added/changed for Neutron.

Closes-Bug: #1247283

Change-Id: I455566455eed4333fb7bd8e74560692ef3e94003

commit_message:
Replace qpid_host with qpid_hostname

This patch replaces `qpid_host` with `qpid_hostname` in both the
qpid manifest and the spec file class. `qpid_host` has been shipped
as the parameter to specify qpid's hostname, although the correct one is
`qpid_hostname`.

Closes-bug 1242715

Change-Id: I92b8da5a204180316f8117634a45154023551abd

commit_message:
Fix neutron tests

* Fix problem with unknown attribute client

commit_message:
Update openstack/common/lockutils

The following commits are in this update:

79e6bc6 fix lockutils.lock() to make it thread-safe
ace5120 Add main() to lockutils that creates temp dir for locks
537d8e2 Allow lockutils to get lock_path conf from envvar
d498c42 Fix to properly log when we release a semaphore
29d387c Add LockFixture to lockutils
3e3ac0c Modify lockutils.py due to dispose of eventlet
90b6a65 Fix locking bug
27d4b41 Move synchronized body to a first-class function
15c17fb Make lock_file_prefix optional
1a2df89 Enable H302 hacking check
b41862d Use param keyword for docstrings

Change-Id: Ic0fb3b7de5817dbd69da761f625689c523932bc4

[{'created': '2013-11-19 17:10:11.000000000', 'message': "Remove in-place try/except blocks from shell commands

Currently we have try/except blocks for each shell command which
may cause an exception, and often we unaware of all possible
exceptions. Therefore our in-place messages may not correspond
to real server exceptions. This patch removes in-place handlers
so shell will rely on single try/except based in
/ironicclient/shell.py: main, which simply prints server's
exception message.

Change-Id: I65dc71c6fb15483fb88ef4c6a423147fe0bb54cb
Closes-Bug: #1251712
"}]
commit_message:
Remove in-place try/except blocks from shell commands

Currently we have try/except blocks for each shell command which
may cause an exception, and often we unaware of all possible
exceptions. Therefore our in-place messages may not correspond
to real server exceptions. This patch removes in-place handlers
so shell will rely on single try/except based in
/ironicclient/shell.py: main, which simply prints server's
exception message.

Change-Id: I65dc71c6fb15483fb88ef4c6a423147fe0bb54cb
Closes-Bug: #1251712

commit_message:
[1247283] Use IP ranges for Public in Neutron

In v.3.2 IP address space for Public network is defined using CIDR.
Now it is defined through IP ranges and network mask.
Some network configuration checks are added/changed for Neutron.

Closes-Bug: #1247283

Change-Id: I455566455eed4333fb7bd8e74560692ef3e94003

commit_message:
Externalisation of heat template

This code piece refactors the earlier code of instance creation
using heat.

Heat templates are stored in /etc/trove/heat_templates/.

For each service type we have a unique template file
<service_type>.heat.template

Change-Id: I430c2c08d514abdf3a6288105b551e78fda814f8
Implements: https://blueprints.launchpad.net/trove/+spec/provide-custom-heat-templates-for-each-service-in-trove

grub components. This change gates that removal on the architecture so that it
skips the step for armhf.

Change-Id: Ie169dbf12213e69b3713b3b1f9a68ae224f9fd31
'}, {'created': '2013-11-19 21:38:44.000000000', 'message': 'Fix issue with Ubuntu grub pre-install step for ARM

The Ubuntu build for ARM breaks when the pre-install step attempts to remove
grub components. This change gates those package removals based on whether
they are currently installed.

Change-Id: Ie169dbf12213e69b3713b3b1f9a68ae224f9fd31
'}]
commit_message:
Fix issue with Ubuntu grub pre-install step for ARM

The Ubuntu build for ARM breaks when the pre-install step attempts to remove
grub components. This change gates those package removals based on whether
they are currently installed.

Change-Id: Ie169dbf12213e69b3713b3b1f9a68ae224f9fd31

commit_message:
Reduce the severity of dhcp related log traces

Due to timing issues, when the agent synchronizes
with the server wrt the representation of server's
and agent's networks, networks may have already
been deleted from the db. In such circumstances,
it is more appropriate to emit warnings rather than
full-blown exceptions as the agent handles these
circumstances just fine.

Close-bug: 1251874

Change-Id: I4b118b6087c7f42226f0d4265d2176c028d99f22

commit_message:
Encode output for fixing UnicodeDecodeError

Current heatclient doesn't handle properly outgoing encode process.
For resolving it, this patch implements a process to encode everything
going out of the client, for example, prints.

This patch used two new modules (gettextutils.py and strutils.py)
taken from oslo-incubator in order to use safe_encode() and
safe_decode().

Closes-Bug: #1249233

Change-Id: Ia8c955a80d68126cd9c1fd791bda3e331a2aa5c9

commit_message:
Check existence of rhel rpm key

The key 'RPM-GPG-KEY-redhat-release' may not exist in image
e.g. when you use non-default image (for example, if you build CentOS
image using rhel element).

Fixes bug #1252697

Change-Id: Iae642abb7a7f76c5528750dafedd4fd4bda56fe2

Based on Winston's comments."}, {'account_id': 7494, 'date': '2013-11-08 04:12:08.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

Thanks all for the comments, but I think its not good to split cinder filters to two places (cinder/openstack/common and scheduler) even though we are using entry point.

Perhaps we can add more filters in oslo and finally move all scheduler filters to cinder/openstack/common, what do you think?'}, {'account_id': 7494, 'date': '2013-11-08 04:13:54.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

Its really bad to maintain similar logic in separated places.'}, {'account_id': 7536, 'date': '2013-11-08 08:23:51.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

I agree with Jay Lau. I don't know reasons not to move all the logically similar functionality to the same place. Huang Zhiteng, it would be fine if you were so kind as to explain these reasons. But I still tend to put one after several changes of which I wrote in comments."}, {'account_id': 7494, 'date': '2013-11-12 04:34:21.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

@Zhiteng, any comments on this? Thanks.'}, {'account_id': 2759, 'date': '2013-11-12 05:48:51.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

First of all, a little bit of history about filter scheduler, Cinder, Nova, Oslo: filter scheduler in Cinder was mostly the same as the one in Nova.  So when it was proposed to be pulled into Cinder, some folks required the common code (scheduler, filters and weighers) to be merged into Oslo first, and then pull that common code into Cinder/Nova so that two projects share the same code.  This was done in late Grizzly cycle and the common code merged into Oslo and then Cinder, but failed to merge in Nova (https://review.openstack.org/#/c/18718/) due to tight schedule and late in release cycle.

Btw, I didn't continue to make changes in Nova during H cycle to make sure it uses the same pieces in Oslo like Cinder does.  That's my bad.

So that explains why there are two separate portion of code for filter scheduler in Cinder.  Also should answer your question why moving the code in cinder/openstack/common/scheduler to cinder/scheduler is a bad idea.

What I suggest, if you wanted to, is to do the exact opposite thing you wanted in Nova, which is to pull common scheduler code from Oslo to Nova and that will make Nova looks exactly the same as Cinder right now."}, {'account_id': 7494, 'date': '2013-11-12 08:39:13.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

Thanks Zhiteng.

Yes, agree with you. I also noticed this part and have logged a bp to put more scheduler to oslo and finally enable nova use scheduler from common.
https://blueprints.launchpad.net/nova/+spec/nova-oslo-scheduler
https://blueprints.launchpad.net/oslo/+spec/oslo-more-filters

I will update the blueprint scheduler-code-refactor to make it reflect what we want to do exactly.'}, {'account_id': 7494, 'date': '2013-11-12 08:43:01.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

commit_message:
Move scheduler filters/weights logic to cinder.scheduler.filters

Some of the filters/weights logic now resides in cinder.openstack.
common.scheduler, but there are also some filters/weights logic
in cinder.scheduler, it is not consistent and difficult to maintain.

Also we should not put filters/weights logic in openstack common as it
is not common code for cinder but special for scheduler, we should
move all of the logic from cinder.openstack.common.scheduler to
cinder.scheduler.

This will make sure cinder.scheduler becomes the central point for
filters/weights logic and can also improve code consistency.

Implements bp scheduler-code-refactor

Change-Id: I682d1c5f3c60efbd258fcc25b5bea4a050fdda00

commit_message:
Recover from deleting state on compute manager start-up

If a compute manager is stopped / fails during a delete operation
then the instance will be left stuck with task_state=deleting

This change treats instances in this state as if they have failed
to delete correctly and triggers the delete again when the compute
manager restarts.

Change-Id: Ic8cb9edbec22d502cdd38444f6e4dd0f0c214b61
Closes-Bug: 1247174

In Grizzly, the version of OVS is lower than 1.9.0. As a result, tunnel
path MTU discovery default value is set to 'enabled'. But internet-wide
path MTU discovery doesn't work all the time, we need to add a
configuration option to disable tunnel path MTU Discovery.

Closes-Bug: 1252603
"}]
commit_message:
Add configuration option to disable tunnel path MTU Discovery

In Grizzly, the version of OVS is lower than 1.9.0. As a result, tunnel
path MTU discovery default value is set to 'enabled'. But internet-wide
path MTU discovery doesn't work all the time, we need to add a
configuration option to disable tunnel path MTU Discovery.

Change-Id: I616d0c95e4c18ea4590eb77aded01687825dd877
Closes-Bug: 1252603

commit_message:
Add devstack integration

Add devstack integration for solum.  Devstack has a plugin mechanism for
unofficial projects to integrate with it without having to change any
of devstack itself.  This commit includes the files and some
instructions on how to use them.

commit_message:
Back-port fix about log from Oslo

Back-port commit 5fef5a8105 allow keeping of existing loggers with
fileconfig.

Currently , common.log.py setup() will disable all existing
loggers that were set up before importing a custom logging
configuration from file. This patch makes disable_existing_loggers
with default value False.

Closes-Bug: #1169328
Closes-Bug: #1238349

Change-Id: I2e565fd65a00f1c6dea830a09487de9f03cb5279

commit_message:
Back-port fix about log from Oslo

Back-port commit 5fef5a8105 allow keeping of existing loggers with
fileconfig.

Currently , common.log.py setup() will disable all existing
loggers that were set up before importing a custom logging
configuration from file. This patch makes disable_existing_loggers
with default value False.

Closes-Bug: #1169328
Closes-Bug: #1238349

Change-Id: I3f58066c6d18477ec7cfcfd610c71baae9b2e21f

revisions:
[{'created': '2013-11-12 14:23:19.000000000', 'message': "Add helper method total_seconds in timeutils.py

Almost every OpenStack project is using hardcode to calculate duration
like 'delta.days * 24 * 3600', even 2592000. Method delta_seconds takes
two timing objects to compute difference between them, total_seconds
wraps that method, only needs time duration input, and can be used like
timeutils.total_seconds(days=1, hours=2)

Change-Id: I397bae402e012c28aaa6aa2bb10170b83eeeaa8c
"}, {'created': '2013-11-14 04:49:54.000000000', 'message': "Add helper method total_seconds in timeutils.py

Almost every OpenStack project is using hardcode to calculate duration
like 'delta.days * 24 * 3600', even 2592000. Method delta_seconds takes
a timedelta instance as input to compute total seconds.

Method delta_seconds also is refactored to call new method.

Change-Id: I397bae402e012c28aaa6aa2bb10170b83eeeaa8c
"}]
commit_message:
Add helper method total_seconds in timeutils.py

Almost every OpenStack project is using hardcode to calculate duration
like 'delta.days * 24 * 3600', even 2592000. Method delta_seconds takes
a timedelta instance as input to compute total seconds.

Method delta_seconds also is refactored to call new method.

Change-Id: I397bae402e012c28aaa6aa2bb10170b83eeeaa8c

Fix GroupAffinityFilter and GroupAntiAffinityFilter doc

The hint key is 'group' and not 'group_hosts', and the hint value is an
arbitrary value and not an instance UUID.

Closes-Bug: #1223242

revisions:
[{'created': '2013-11-08 10:50:07.000000000', 'message': 'Add a check for newline after docstring summary

The style guide says:

"""A multi line docstring has a one-line summary, less than 80 characters.

Then a new paragraph after a newline that explains in more detail any
general information about the function, class or method.
[...]

but hacking only checks that the text of the docstring starts
immediately after """.  It would be nice to check for the existence of
that empty line separating the summary from the rest of the comment.

Change-Id: I331a0f417f97784c083c06fb2fa18b384d8ed497
Closes-bug: #1249287
'}]
commit_message:
Add a check for newline after docstring summary

The style guide says:

"""A multi line docstring has a one-line summary, less than 80 characters.

Then a new paragraph after a newline that explains in more detail any
general information about the function, class or method.
[...]

but hacking only checks that the text of the docstring starts
immediately after """.  It would be nice to check for the existence of
that empty line separating the summary from the rest of the comment.

Change-Id: I331a0f417f97784c083c06fb2fa18b384d8ed497
Closes-bug: #1249287

commit_message:
Removed references to unused  libvirt_ovs_bridge flag.

The libvirt_ovs_bridge flag was unused in the code and removed under bug
1251813. This update removes it from the configuration mapping and the
current output (I didn't want to regenerate the entire configuration
tables this early in the cycle to avoid impacting backports too badly).

Change-Id: I91f6e58a7190279447a0f9439f7e30d662e7befd
Closes-Bug: #1251813

Added missing python-novaclient installation

installation, required to complete the procedure.

backport: havana
Closes-Bug: #1252604

commit_message:
Add Swift as backup backend support

Cinder can backup volumes in different backends.
Swift will be the first one supported by puppet-cinder.

New class: cinder::backup::swift

Change-Id: Iec0a48681da8fd987955cabae49d411ede1e255e
Signed-off-by: Emilien Macchi <emilien.macchi@enovance.com>

commit_message:
Attempt to resolve a "database is locked" error

https://bugs.launchpad.net/swift/+bug/1224253 is the issue. I don't
understand the mechanism of action here, but this brings the behvior
closer to the original code, while still retaining the explicit closing
needed for PyPy.

Change-Id: I11347fc560a8885d386afdf0fd7598d3b4b73062

The token backend configuration option for Keystone only allowed
kvs or sql and not the memcache backend.

This change allows users to set
 KEYSTONE_TOKEN_BACKEND=memcache
in localrc to use the memcache backend.

This makes it easier to use the memcache token backend with
Keystone.

Change-Id: I341aaf74d2e648eec8da0a36e80a51d2d97f6ecb
'}]
commit_message:
Keystone allow memcache for token backend

The token backend configuration option for Keystone only allowed
kvs or sql and not the memcache backend.

This change allows users to set
 KEYSTONE_TOKEN_BACKEND=memcache
in localrc to use the memcache backend.

This makes it easier to use the memcache token backend with
Keystone.

Change-Id: I341aaf74d2e648eec8da0a36e80a51d2d97f6ecb

commit_message:
LBaaS: fix reported binary name of a loadbalancer agent

Loadbalancer agent's actual binary name differs from what it reports
to Neutron server, so need to fix:
neutron-loadbalancer-agent -> neutron-lbaas-agent

Closes-Bug: #1248222
Change-Id: Ic4e05d0258ba8eb48b96c60d69c1dbf9f27731f6

commit_message:
Correct name of Ceilometer central agent service for Fedora and EL

Fedora and EL-based operating systems use the name
"openstack-ceilometer-central" for this service rather than
"openstack-ceilometer-agent-central.

As such while there is overlap with the instructions for openSUSE and
SLES this slight difference needs to be accounted for.

Change-Id: I8f922cafd35e1eedfa8d00f14cf07acbeefe842f
backport: havana
Closes-Bug: #1252265

commit_message:
Don't use duplicate IP addresses

Neutron is going to start rejecting attempts to create multiple members
in the same pool with duplicate IP address/port tuples.  This change
updates the tempest gate to make it stop trying to create new members
with the same IP address.

Change-Id: Ib0b14145a5c88127151ae036147e7c5c35436fa1
Closes-Bug: #1252834

commit_message:
Add jenkins-job-builder as a broken out project

There is a wholly separate dev community around jenkins-job-builder
that it would be nice to track. Leaving jjb also in infra though,
because it's interesting to track there as well.

Change-Id: I61f29f78bb6300f9b0c9fe9522172f090234f0b9

commit_message:
Improve multi DHCP agent support

Since Grizzly release, a specific number of DHCP agents can be scheduled to host a
network.
This enables redundant DHCP agents for configured networks.

Change-Id: I3388282c0a46eafa2b4e0e6d2d0293fa91e46cc3
Signed-off-by: Emilien Macchi <emilien.macchi@enovance.com>

Max, yes, this H302 is new rule from our gate-ironic-pep8, so if it is enabled, we can not import a single module "_" directly, have to import gettextutils, and call with "gettextutils._".
I checked othere project, there is no such issue, because no need to add new "gettextutils" as import, and our gate-ironic-pep8 just check the 'Changed' code, so that is our situation here.'}, {'account_id': 8106, 'date': '2013-11-15 23:30:25.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

Looks like it is working now, how do you think for this patch?'}, {'account_id': 8968, 'date': '2013-11-18 10:06:07.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: No score

Hi Haomeng,

Let's discuss with the team in IRC. I think "ignore H302" is right way to do that

Thanks'}, {'account_id': 2889, 'date': '2013-11-18 22:59:36.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

Good catch! However, we should continue to import and use "_" rather than "gettext._"

Since we need to import it explicitly to fix these errors, and we don't necessarily want to blanket-ignore H302, try this:

  from ironic.openstack.common.gettextutils import _ # noqa

For reference, this is being used throughout Oslo now.'}, {'account_id': 8106, 'date': '2013-11-19 01:49:56.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

missing gettext _ to fix such Sphinx error with this patch.

commit_message:
Import missing gettext _ to fix Sphinx error

We run "python setup.py build_sphinx" to generate the API documents,
however encountered a lot of "NameError: name '_' is not defined",
which will cause our api.controllers.v1.* objects documents will not
be generated by Sphinx, so we are missing these in the document page
http://docs.openstack.org/developer/ironic/py-modindex.html. Import
missing gettext _ to fix such Sphinx error with this patch.

Change-Id: Ie53d96203109b8b95b9734b58d85da41a2d011cf
Closes-Bug: #1251011

commit_message:
Redefined default value of allowed_rpc_exception_modules

Redefined allowed_rpc_exception_modules in ironic code since initial
setting is set in Oslo (ironic.openstack.common.rpc.__init__). This
will force RPC exception deserialization work with Ironic exceptions
instead of RemoteError.

Change-Id: Ibb10dc5d0dd58ae407980d97bd4f86ed22c7988b
Closes-Bug: #1250575

commit_message:
Update openstack/common/lockutils

79e6bc6 fix lockutils.lock() to make it thread-safe
ace5120 Add main() to lockutils that creates temp dir for locks
537d8e2 Allow lockutils to get lock_path conf from envvar
d498c42 Fix to properly log when we release a semaphore
29d387c Add LockFixture to lockutils
3e3ac0c Modify lockutils.py due to dispose of eventlet
90b6a65 Fix locking bug
27d4b41 Move synchronized body to a first-class function
15c17fb Make lock_file_prefix optional
1a2df89 Enable H302 hacking check
b41862d Use param keyword for docstrings

Change-Id: Id604ae4188ebf822746e229165e7fcdb78a66f96

revisions:
[{'created': '2013-11-19 17:15:31.000000000', 'message': 'Add SLDs that act like TLDs

This change is from the Icehouse release.  The effective TLD file need
not
be present.  When it is not present the behavior would be the same as
before.  When it is present, the domains that are being created are
checked
to see that it is not an effective TLD.

This change offers the designate administrator the ability to configure
2 lists to indicate the TLDs(accepted_tlds_file) and SLDs and others
that
effectively act as TLDs.(effective_tlds_file)

2 sample files are included to show the format required for these files.
The TLD file is from http://data.iana.org/TLD/tlds-alpha-by-domain.txt
Commented lines in this file begin with a #. There is one entry per line
and the entries are in the IDNA format.

The sample effective TLD file is from http://publicsuffix.org/list/
This file is in the UTF-8 format.  Lines beginning with a // and ! are
ignored.  The wildcard character * (asterisk) may only be used to
wildcard
the topmost level in a domain name.  All the entries  are converted to
idna format.

Change-Id: I428263f4812613383d93c31cfe6ad6f7d9fda0e7
Closes-Bug: #1249396
'}]
commit_message:
Add SLDs that act like TLDs

This change is from the Icehouse release.  The effective TLD file need
not
be present.  When it is not present the behavior would be the same as
before.  When it is present, the domains that are being created are
checked
to see that it is not an effective TLD.

This change offers the designate administrator the ability to configure
2 lists to indicate the TLDs(accepted_tlds_file) and SLDs and others
that
effectively act as TLDs.(effective_tlds_file)

2 sample files are included to show the format required for these files.
The TLD file is from http://data.iana.org/TLD/tlds-alpha-by-domain.txt
Commented lines in this file begin with a #. There is one entry per line
and the entries are in the IDNA format.

The sample effective TLD file is from http://publicsuffix.org/list/
This file is in the UTF-8 format.  Lines beginning with a // and ! are
ignored.  The wildcard character * (asterisk) may only be used to
wildcard
the topmost level in a domain name.  All the entries  are converted to
idna format.

Change-Id: I428263f4812613383d93c31cfe6ad6f7d9fda0e7
Closes-Bug: #1249396

commit_message:
Fix none expected_task_state for instance.save()

Currently when invoking instance.save() with expected_task_state as None,
the instance object assumes ignore it, this is different with
previous assumption.

Change the caller to passing a tuple with None to resolve this issue.

Change-Id: If1c67f72eefdf9a8ea63a30b6503e4727bcd3c79

commit_message:
Adding qpid support to nova

Moving all qpid parameters under default["openstack"]["compute"]["mq"]["qpid"]
so that other qpid options can be added under it. Rabbit parameters
will be brought under "mq" eventually. MQ is selected through
default["openstack"]["compute"]["mq"]["service_type"]. Default is
"rabbit"

Change-Id: Iecec7a851652b82fb58d38081d483a7b13e92402
Implements: blueprint qpid-activemq-support

[{'created': '2013-11-19 15:55:55.000000000', 'message': 'fix: import-time side effect on errors

A subtle module mismatch occurs when importing:

    from marconiclient.transport import errors

This actually brings in marconiclient.errors, rather than the expected
marconiclient.transport.errors. This patch addresses the issue, which
was caused by import-time side effects in
marconiclient.transport.__init__.

Change-Id: I2209193fc81099b1af3e0fc174b254cdfcfc619a
'}]
commit_message:
fix: import-time side effect on errors

A subtle module mismatch occurs when importing:

    from marconiclient.transport import errors

This actually brings in marconiclient.errors, rather than the expected
marconiclient.transport.errors. This patch addresses the issue, which
was caused by import-time side effects in
marconiclient.transport.__init__.

Change-Id: I2209193fc81099b1af3e0fc174b254cdfcfc619a

commit_message:
Abstract creation of a deployment engine

Introduced the factory function to create engines in the
rally.deploy.engine module.

This patch also covers changes by extending of unit tests.

Change-Id: Ia614c71b34c18e5fb09760c82a144262d5284501
Implements: blueprint independent-deploy

[{'created': '2013-11-19 15:44:52.000000000', 'message': 'fix: import-time side effect on errors

commit_message:
fix: import-time side effect on errors

A subtle module mismatch occurs when importing:

    from marconiclient.transport import errors

This actually brings in marconiclient.errors, rather than the expected
marconiclient.transport.errors. This patch addresses the issue, which
was caused by import-time side effects in
marconiclient.transport.__init__.

Change-Id: I9b3d8d8540c554e4c63f3317ec80b190e42d17fa

[{'account_id': 8864, 'date': '2013-11-11 19:53:50.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

To summarize what was said in the IRC channel (and to keep discussion centralized and easy to find and follow):

1. My opinion (for what it's worth) is that this seems like the kind of thing that should be split off into a separate module altogether, or at least its own class/component within Designate. Central would just call is_effective_tld(suffix) for example.

2. There was debate around how to ship and keep current the list. There are multiple sources (IANA, Mozilla's publicsuffix). Do we ship the files with Desigante? Do we update them from the 'net? If the latter, how often? Also if the latter, operators should probably have the option to override/modify the lists and to control when it gets updated from the 'net.

My 0.62 rubles ;)"}, {'account_id': 741, 'date': '2013-11-12 11:17:43.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

I think having a database table for something as static as these seems excessive, and when we eventually get around to implementing live config reloading, we can do the same with these lists.. 

It's disappointing that none of the public suffix libraries on pypi are useful :( Oh well.

I like artom's idea from IRC, where we turn the bulk of this into a module on it's own (e.g designate/publicsuffix.py) - central/service.py is getting HUGE, and is due some refactoring anyway.. Let's not add more work to the pile :)

I think "public suffix" is a suitable name for handling both the Mozilla and IANA lists, as it's descriptive of intent rather than the source of the information.

Re including in-tree - I've done some research, and I believe we can include both IANA and Mozilla lists in-tree.. The IANA list is public domain, and the Mozilla list is MPL 2.0. See [1].

Finally, if we want to merge this into the "stable/havana" branch, we need to avoid changing the existing default behaviors. Having 2 config options for "Use IANA list" and "Use Public Suffix list", both enabled by default in master, and only the IANA one enabled in stable/havana is probably the way to go.

[1]: http://www.mozilla.org/MPL/2.0/FAQ.html#mpl-bsd-and-apache'}, {'account_id': 8094, 'date': '2013-11-12 20:37:08.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

I moved the tld related code to a separate module - central/effectivetld.py to reflect its intent.

As for punycode - I found that encoding the publicsuffix list to idna works correctly.  If I encode it to punycode, it does not put the "xn--" prefix.  Additionally in punycode normal ascii strings are suffixed with a -.  With the idna format everything works as expected.'}, {'account_id': 8094, 'date': '2013-11-12 20:37:29.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 8094, 'date': '2013-11-12 20:39:13.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 3.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-11-12 20:40:39.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3: Doesn't seem to work

The SLD list is from publicsuffix.org.  This needs to be present at
etc/designate/effective_tld_names.dat.  This is parsed so that lines

commit_message:
Add SLDs that act like TLDs

This change offers the designate administrator the ability to configure
2 lists to indicate the TLDs(accepted_tlds_file) and SLDs and others
that
effectively act as TLDs.(effective_tlds_file)

2 sample files are included to show the format required for these files.
The TLD file is from http://data.iana.org/TLD/tlds-alpha-by-domain.txt
Commented lines in this file begin with a #. There is one entry per line
and the entries are in the IDNA format.

The sample effective TLD file is from http://publicsuffix.org/list/
This file is in the UTF-8 format.  Lines beginning with a // and ! are
ignored.  The wildcard character * (asterisk) may only be used to
wildcard
the topmost level in a domain name.  All the entries  are converted to
idna format.

Closes-Bug: #1249396

Change-Id: I9718489335e24cb24733d4c4fc2a966e490014d3

commit_message:
Fix cpu_quota setting

After I30e550d21f00eb949ee2f3f8fb4d952c10bf8000, cpu_quota setting
(cpu_shares, cpu_quota, cpu_period) needs "quota" namespace.
If not specifying the namespace when customizing flavor, the quota
does not work.
This patch fixes the description.

Change-Id: I6dd8e921db665c62d5039283ec0ed2c433ccad2e

commit_message:
Fix debian/ubuntu related issues

In course of time, apt database goes outdated, and 404 errors occured
when attempting to apt-get install. So, before doing apt-get install,
apt-get update is needed.

Change-Id: Ibe79b692d33e641d8c521c4ef58c5db7e991536a

commit_message:
Fix troubleshooting override.

We can now actually override the $TROUBLESHOOT environment variable in
ramdisks, by not declaring it as readonly. Yay for insufficient
end-to-end testing.

Change-Id: I3a2af3f40486cc5b832d4b1bc7067df655859cdb

commit_message:
Update openstack/common/lockutils

The following commits are in this update:

79e6bc6 fix lockutils.lock() to make it thread-safe
ace5120 Add main() to lockutils that creates temp dir for locks
537d8e2 Allow lockutils to get lock_path conf from envvar
d498c42 Fix to properly log when we release a semaphore

Change-Id: Ida26987e8841d79f3d4627d7f46ab08eb59234ec
